WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:07.410 --> 00:00:11.060
SCOTT WIENER: Maybe about a
year, year and a half ago, I

00:00:11.060 --> 00:00:11.660
took what I do--

00:00:11.660 --> 00:00:14.720
I mean, what I do for the most
part is I'm just obsessed with

00:00:14.720 --> 00:00:18.320
pizza the way that any
normal human is.

00:00:18.320 --> 00:00:20.350
You like to eat pizza, you
see boxes of pizza, you

00:00:20.350 --> 00:00:21.770
want to dive in.

00:00:21.770 --> 00:00:24.950
It sort of decomposes
every human.

00:00:24.950 --> 00:00:29.000
When a box of pizza comes out,
you go back to 12 years old,

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:31.040
and that's sort of it, and it's
always going to happen

00:00:31.040 --> 00:00:32.020
for your whole life.

00:00:32.020 --> 00:00:33.640
It's just this thing
that embodies the

00:00:33.640 --> 00:00:35.300
spirit, I think, of youth.

00:00:35.300 --> 00:00:37.970
And in a lot of ways, we're
going to talk about why that

00:00:37.970 --> 00:00:40.430
happens all day today.

00:00:40.430 --> 00:00:43.050
Today what I want to do is I
want to take you through what

00:00:43.050 --> 00:00:45.970
we're eating, talk about where
it comes from, what it is and

00:00:45.970 --> 00:00:48.730
what it means and where it's
going, just because around New

00:00:48.730 --> 00:00:51.070
York City, there's so many
different styles of pizza.

00:00:51.070 --> 00:00:53.280
And the first thing that ever
happens when I walk in a room

00:00:53.280 --> 00:00:55.110
and I'm like, oh, we're going
to be talking about pizza,

00:00:55.110 --> 00:00:58.720
everybody starts asking
questions about, what's the

00:00:58.720 --> 00:01:00.880
best, what's your favorite,
that kind of thing.

00:01:00.880 --> 00:01:02.910
I just want to let you guys know
we're not talking about

00:01:02.910 --> 00:01:03.750
that today.

00:01:03.750 --> 00:01:07.140
That's just to clear the air,
because we could spend three

00:01:07.140 --> 00:01:09.010
hours sitting here going around
the room and everybody

00:01:09.010 --> 00:01:10.490
being like, well, what
about this place?

00:01:10.490 --> 00:01:11.360
Isn't it the best?

00:01:11.360 --> 00:01:12.810
As I was walking up here--

00:01:12.810 --> 00:01:15.320
so I do walking tours
and bus tours.

00:01:15.320 --> 00:01:19.210
And the guy who runs the bus
squad out of nowhere text

00:01:19.210 --> 00:01:23.640
messages me, hey, in your
opinion, just a question,

00:01:23.640 --> 00:01:25.870
what's the best pizza
in New York?

00:01:25.870 --> 00:01:30.020
I'm like, you couldn't get any
worse of a question than that.

00:01:30.020 --> 00:01:34.490
Just because when you guys go
out and eat pizza, I feel like

00:01:34.490 --> 00:01:36.690
the first decision that you're
making when you're picking a

00:01:36.690 --> 00:01:40.280
place to go is you're
choosing proximity.

00:01:40.280 --> 00:01:41.790
A lot of times it's like, what's
in this neighborhood,

00:01:41.790 --> 00:01:42.620
what's the deal with that?

00:01:42.620 --> 00:01:44.670
It's very rare that you're ever
in a situation where,

00:01:44.670 --> 00:01:47.660
like, we're going to go anywhere
within 15 miles.

00:01:47.660 --> 00:01:49.280
Let's pick one and we're
all going to

00:01:49.280 --> 00:01:50.660
rent a car or something.

00:01:50.660 --> 00:01:52.440
That's a lot more rare.

00:01:52.440 --> 00:01:54.400
But if you ever do that,
you've probably--

00:01:54.400 --> 00:01:57.610
I mean, I've been in the
same boat many times.

00:01:57.610 --> 00:02:00.920
You're picking places sort
of based on adventure.

00:02:00.920 --> 00:02:04.810
Right now in New York, we're
in this amazing position of

00:02:04.810 --> 00:02:08.110
having so many pizza styles
happening all at one time.

00:02:08.110 --> 00:02:12.020
Whereas in the past, when you
think of New York style pizza,

00:02:12.020 --> 00:02:13.450
there's certainly New
York style pizza

00:02:13.450 --> 00:02:14.520
sitting on this table.

00:02:14.520 --> 00:02:16.850
New York Pizza Suprema is the
name of one of the pizzerias

00:02:16.850 --> 00:02:18.180
that brought some pies.

00:02:18.180 --> 00:02:20.270
That's a classic
New York pizza.

00:02:20.270 --> 00:02:24.720
Then we have Donatella, which
is on 8th Avenue and I think

00:02:24.720 --> 00:02:28.270
19th Street, 18th Street,
and that's not a

00:02:28.270 --> 00:02:29.230
typical New York pizza.

00:02:29.230 --> 00:02:30.730
That's a pre-New York pizza.

00:02:30.730 --> 00:02:32.010
It's a Neapolitan pizza.

00:02:32.010 --> 00:02:33.840
Then we also have John's, which
I think is all the way

00:02:33.840 --> 00:02:35.160
down at that end of the table.

00:02:35.160 --> 00:02:36.970
I think it's already all gone.

00:02:36.970 --> 00:02:38.360
Is there any John's left?

00:02:38.360 --> 00:02:40.180
There's two slices left?

00:02:40.180 --> 00:02:40.880
From what pie?

00:02:40.880 --> 00:02:41.860
AUDIENCE: Mushroom.

00:02:41.860 --> 00:02:43.350
SCOTT WIENER: Both mushroom?

00:02:43.350 --> 00:02:45.000
No love for the mushroom.

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:46.670
Although now that you announced
it, now everyone's

00:02:46.670 --> 00:02:47.590
going to be running over.

00:02:47.590 --> 00:02:49.620
Well, so we've got a couple of
slices from John's, and John's

00:02:49.620 --> 00:02:51.370
is somewhere in between
those two.

00:02:51.370 --> 00:02:53.760
And I'm not talking about
quality-wise.

00:02:53.760 --> 00:02:57.200
I'm not talking about that one
is the best and the other is a

00:02:57.200 --> 00:02:57.700
lower quality.

00:02:57.700 --> 00:03:00.550
I'm talking about historically,
just because as

00:03:00.550 --> 00:03:03.530
you go through time, you find
developments from one style to

00:03:03.530 --> 00:03:07.155
another and the developments
all happen mainly

00:03:07.155 --> 00:03:08.990
for economic reasons.

00:03:08.990 --> 00:03:14.080
History, economics, and social
positioning really have a lot

00:03:14.080 --> 00:03:16.490
to do with pizza styles
changing.

00:03:16.490 --> 00:03:17.380
So I'm just curious.

00:03:17.380 --> 00:03:22.140
Just right off the bat, does
anybody have a current

00:03:22.140 --> 00:03:26.700
favorite pizzeria anywhere
at all in the world?

00:03:26.700 --> 00:03:27.310
What do you got?

00:03:27.310 --> 00:03:28.040
AUDIENCE: Bar in New Haven.

00:03:28.040 --> 00:03:29.020
SCOTT WIENER: Bar
in New Haven.

00:03:29.020 --> 00:03:31.800
Bar is an interesting place,
because Bar opened about 15

00:03:31.800 --> 00:03:34.000
years ago, and they're
in New Haven.

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:36.060
And if anybody's been in New
Haven, Connecticut, New Haven

00:03:36.060 --> 00:03:37.940
is like a stronghold
for pizza.

00:03:37.940 --> 00:03:41.920
It's the kind of place where
sometimes I hear people say,

00:03:41.920 --> 00:03:45.145
oh, I heard New Haven actually
has the oldest pizzerias in

00:03:45.145 --> 00:03:48.690
the United States, which is not
really true, but New Haven

00:03:48.690 --> 00:03:50.070
has a lot of really old ones.

00:03:50.070 --> 00:03:52.870
They have got a place Frank
Pepe's, which opened in 1925,

00:03:52.870 --> 00:03:54.970
and then down the street there's
a place that Frank

00:03:54.970 --> 00:03:58.280
Pepe's nephews, Tony and
Salvatore, opened a place in

00:03:58.280 --> 00:04:00.010
1938 called Sally's.

00:04:00.010 --> 00:04:02.580
And these are these two big
places in New Haven that if

00:04:02.580 --> 00:04:04.640
you live or if you've ever been
in New Haven or if your

00:04:04.640 --> 00:04:07.840
family grew up there or
anything, everybody has one or

00:04:07.840 --> 00:04:09.100
the other that they love.

00:04:09.100 --> 00:04:13.340
Then in comes Bar 15 years
ago, and they do a very

00:04:13.340 --> 00:04:14.480
non-traditional pizza.

00:04:14.480 --> 00:04:16.420
Everybody who goes there really
loves the-- and I don't

00:04:16.420 --> 00:04:18.370
know if you fall into
this category--

00:04:18.370 --> 00:04:19.680
mashed potato pizza.

00:04:19.680 --> 00:04:22.110
If you are in that category,
that's cool.

00:04:22.110 --> 00:04:25.960
Totally atypical, totally a
non-classic, nontraditional

00:04:25.960 --> 00:04:29.680
pizza, but absolutely valid in
the eyes of the great pizza

00:04:29.680 --> 00:04:32.100
landscape, because you can
really put anything on pizza

00:04:32.100 --> 00:04:34.550
and it still counts
as that category.

00:04:34.550 --> 00:04:35.820
So Bar is an interesting one.

00:04:35.820 --> 00:04:38.290
I'm glad that you brought that
up, because it sort of crosses

00:04:38.290 --> 00:04:38.650
boundaries.

00:04:38.650 --> 00:04:41.480
Well, we're going to talk
about these three main

00:04:41.480 --> 00:04:45.060
staples, these three strata,
these bits of the evolutionary

00:04:45.060 --> 00:04:45.995
process within pizza.

00:04:45.995 --> 00:04:48.700
And then there are some places
like Bar that don't

00:04:48.700 --> 00:04:50.330
fit right into it.

00:04:50.330 --> 00:04:51.770
Any other favorites?

00:04:51.770 --> 00:04:52.560
Like, what do you got?

00:04:52.560 --> 00:04:54.176
AUDIENCE: Pizza Modo
[INAUDIBLE].

00:04:54.176 --> 00:04:55.450
SCOTT WIENER: Pizza Modo--

00:04:55.450 --> 00:05:00.060
David with the outdoor oven
thing, and he's got a few now.

00:05:00.060 --> 00:05:03.380
And David's really interesting
because Pizza Modo is a

00:05:03.380 --> 00:05:07.330
portable, wood-fired oven, and
he'll bring it to street fairs

00:05:07.330 --> 00:05:09.610
and things like that, and
bakes these incredible

00:05:09.610 --> 00:05:10.820
Neapolitan pizzas.

00:05:10.820 --> 00:05:13.750
That's more similar to
Donatella, except for the

00:05:13.750 --> 00:05:17.940
beauty of a place like Pizza
Modo is that you're outside,

00:05:17.940 --> 00:05:19.590
he's going to hand you the
pizza, it's never going to get

00:05:19.590 --> 00:05:20.560
trapped in a box.

00:05:20.560 --> 00:05:22.410
If we could have had these
delivered here without those

00:05:22.410 --> 00:05:25.430
boxes, that would've been
amazing, but we didn't,

00:05:25.430 --> 00:05:27.630
because Greg has two arms
and that's about it.

00:05:27.630 --> 00:05:28.680
But what else?

00:05:28.680 --> 00:05:29.480
Any other favorites?

00:05:29.480 --> 00:05:32.160
So far we've hit two totally
different strata.

00:05:32.160 --> 00:05:32.590
What do you got?

00:05:32.590 --> 00:05:35.090
AUDIENCE: Pi Pizzeria
in Washington, DC.

00:05:35.090 --> 00:05:37.130
SCOTT WIENER: Is that the
full name of it, Pi?

00:05:37.130 --> 00:05:39.420
AUDIENCE: It's called
Pi [INAUDIBLE].

00:05:39.420 --> 00:05:41.630
SCOTT WIENER: Oh, gotcha.

00:05:41.630 --> 00:05:44.000
Just so you guys know, it should
be pretty obvious,

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:48.650
there are, like, 50 places
called Pi with the pi symbol

00:05:48.650 --> 00:05:49.470
and they're not related.

00:05:49.470 --> 00:05:54.630
It's sort of like what Ray's
is to New York, Pi is to

00:05:54.630 --> 00:05:55.720
everyone else around
the country.

00:05:55.720 --> 00:05:57.040
Everyone's like, oh, here's
a really cute,

00:05:57.040 --> 00:05:58.460
quirky name for a pizzeria--

00:05:58.460 --> 00:05:59.240
pi.

00:05:59.240 --> 00:06:01.630
And I actually know somebody who
owns a place called Pi in

00:06:01.630 --> 00:06:06.000
Rochester, Minnesota, and
it's the pi symbol.

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:07.320
But anyway, I haven't
been to that place.

00:06:07.320 --> 00:06:08.070
What's the style?

00:06:08.070 --> 00:06:09.890
AUDIENCE: Lower Chicago style.

00:06:09.890 --> 00:06:10.195
SCOTT WIENER: Really?

00:06:10.195 --> 00:06:11.260
AUDIENCE: But not
overly cheesy.

00:06:11.260 --> 00:06:12.850
SCOTT WIENER: Is it Chicago
thin crust or

00:06:12.850 --> 00:06:13.845
Chicago deep dish?

00:06:13.845 --> 00:06:16.540
AUDIENCE: They call
it Chicago style.

00:06:16.540 --> 00:06:17.992
It's allegedly [INAUDIBLE].

00:06:21.864 --> 00:06:25.252
It was the first pizza place
I found [INAUDIBLE]

00:06:25.252 --> 00:06:25.736
proximity.

00:06:25.736 --> 00:06:27.180
SCOTT WIENER: Proximity.

00:06:27.180 --> 00:06:30.050
So proximity is a huge
factor in the whole

00:06:30.050 --> 00:06:31.120
discussion of pizza.

00:06:31.120 --> 00:06:35.820
The origin of pizza has nothing
to do with anything

00:06:35.820 --> 00:06:39.660
besides proximity, because the
way we're going to track these

00:06:39.660 --> 00:06:42.480
three different types of pizza
are basically through the

00:06:42.480 --> 00:06:44.830
ovens that they're using,
through the cheeses that

00:06:44.830 --> 00:06:47.200
they're using, the machinery
that's available that they're

00:06:47.200 --> 00:06:49.850
using in the kitchens, and
I think that might be it.

00:06:49.850 --> 00:06:51.140
There's no fourth one,
but we'll see.

00:06:51.140 --> 00:06:53.160
So this is actually a good
place to start, because I

00:06:53.160 --> 00:06:55.580
brought some photos of things,
just photos that I've taken

00:06:55.580 --> 00:06:58.440
over the years, to try to
help explain some of the

00:06:58.440 --> 00:07:00.270
progression of what we
have on the table.

00:07:00.270 --> 00:07:02.180
And the first one, the first
pizza, that we're going to

00:07:02.180 --> 00:07:06.330
talk about is that, like,
Pizza Modo, it's this

00:07:06.330 --> 00:07:08.180
Neapolitan pizza
from Donatella.

00:07:08.180 --> 00:07:09.160
Yeah, so do me a favor.

00:07:09.160 --> 00:07:11.390
Somebody just hold that up a
little bit, just so everyone

00:07:11.390 --> 00:07:13.630
knows what I'm talking about.

00:07:13.630 --> 00:07:16.255
And at this point,
there's so many--

00:07:16.255 --> 00:07:17.830
oh, is that the sausage
[INAUDIBLE]?

00:07:17.830 --> 00:07:18.490
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:07:18.490 --> 00:07:19.130
SCOTT WIENER: Cool.

00:07:19.130 --> 00:07:20.870
At some point, just pass
that this way.

00:07:20.870 --> 00:07:21.750
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:21.750 --> 00:07:23.070
AUDIENCE: You want
it right now?

00:07:23.070 --> 00:07:25.770
SCOTT WIENER: Yeah, let's
do it right now.

00:07:25.770 --> 00:07:26.570
Oh, thank you.

00:07:26.570 --> 00:07:30.790
Wow, you're like the doctor in
the delivery room handing me

00:07:30.790 --> 00:07:33.980
my first child.

00:07:33.980 --> 00:07:34.430
This is great.

00:07:34.430 --> 00:07:37.660
Well, so at this point in human
history, especially in

00:07:37.660 --> 00:07:41.070
New York, so many articles
are written about

00:07:41.070 --> 00:07:41.950
pizza all the time.

00:07:41.950 --> 00:07:44.560
And Neapolitan is sort of like
a big focus in it, but I want

00:07:44.560 --> 00:07:46.400
to really concentrate
on what that means.

00:07:46.400 --> 00:07:49.160
Sometimes people look at a pizza
like this and they say,

00:07:49.160 --> 00:07:52.990
oh, this is a gourmet pizza,
oh, this is a highfalutin,

00:07:52.990 --> 00:07:54.130
fancy pants pizza.

00:07:54.130 --> 00:07:56.680
The interesting thing about it
is this is the oldest form of

00:07:56.680 --> 00:07:58.720
pizza, this is the
original format.

00:07:58.720 --> 00:08:01.990
And the original format of
oven are these giant--

00:08:01.990 --> 00:08:03.260
well, not so giant--

00:08:03.260 --> 00:08:04.880
these big wood-burning ovens.

00:08:04.880 --> 00:08:06.830
And you've seen them
all over the place.

00:08:06.830 --> 00:08:10.150
This is not your first time
seeing a wood-burning oven.

00:08:10.150 --> 00:08:12.480
But other wood-burning
ovens around city--

00:08:12.480 --> 00:08:17.970
Don Antonio, Keste, Motorino,
Paulie Gee's in Greenpoint,

00:08:17.970 --> 00:08:18.760
Fornino in Williamsburg.

00:08:18.760 --> 00:08:20.660
I mean, they're all
over the place.

00:08:20.660 --> 00:08:22.530
We could go on for an hour
listing them all.

00:08:22.530 --> 00:08:24.815
And this oven is really
important for what we were

00:08:24.815 --> 00:08:27.760
just talking about with
proximity, because the oven is

00:08:27.760 --> 00:08:29.300
the whole reason that
pizza exists.

00:08:29.300 --> 00:08:33.710
In the early 16th century, early
1500s, we have these

00:08:33.710 --> 00:08:35.840
ovens, or baker's ovens,
and they're

00:08:35.840 --> 00:08:37.539
wood-burning baker's ovens.

00:08:37.539 --> 00:08:39.880
And you can find these going
all the way back to being

00:08:39.880 --> 00:08:43.150
baker's ovens back to 2,000
years ago in Pompeii.

00:08:43.150 --> 00:08:45.870
If you ever go to Pompeii or
Herculaneum, you can find, I

00:08:45.870 --> 00:08:50.720
think, 30 or 40 of these ovens
sitting around preserved,

00:08:50.720 --> 00:08:51.430
these ovens.

00:08:51.430 --> 00:08:53.410
And the way that they work
is they're real simple.

00:08:53.410 --> 00:08:55.070
We're going to get to the
functionality a little bit

00:08:55.070 --> 00:08:57.300
later, but all you need to
understand is, it's a

00:08:57.300 --> 00:08:58.100
wood-burning oven.

00:08:58.100 --> 00:09:00.790
They use wood, they fire it up,
they get the oven chamber

00:09:00.790 --> 00:09:01.780
really hot.

00:09:01.780 --> 00:09:04.830
And once that chamber reaches
what they call a soak point,

00:09:04.830 --> 00:09:07.800
that soak point is where the
stone within the oven, the

00:09:07.800 --> 00:09:10.380
masonry within the oven, has
enough power, has enough

00:09:10.380 --> 00:09:13.250
thermal energy, that it can
continuously bake product

00:09:13.250 --> 00:09:15.490
throughout the day without
a live fire.

00:09:15.490 --> 00:09:17.770
And that's important, because
once you have a fire in there

00:09:17.770 --> 00:09:20.200
like they do in this photo,
you can't bake anything

00:09:20.200 --> 00:09:22.020
directly next to that fire.

00:09:22.020 --> 00:09:25.460
If you let the fire burn out,
and let the oven kind of even

00:09:25.460 --> 00:09:28.000
out at its soak point,
then you can use any

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:29.410
spot within the oven.

00:09:29.410 --> 00:09:30.820
So that's what bakers did.

00:09:30.820 --> 00:09:34.920
Bakers would just use the oven
at soak point to bake anywhere

00:09:34.920 --> 00:09:35.610
within the oven.

00:09:35.610 --> 00:09:38.950
But in the beginning of each
baking session, to test the

00:09:38.950 --> 00:09:40.860
oven to see if it was hot
enough, they would take a

00:09:40.860 --> 00:09:43.320
piece of dough from yesterday
and they would flatten it out

00:09:43.320 --> 00:09:45.660
and toss it inside the oven
just to see if the

00:09:45.660 --> 00:09:46.340
oven was real hot.

00:09:46.340 --> 00:09:48.300
And if the oven's hot enough,
then that dough is going to

00:09:48.300 --> 00:09:50.500
blister and it's going to start
to rise and it's going

00:09:50.500 --> 00:09:53.220
to take about two, two and a
half minutes before it's

00:09:53.220 --> 00:09:55.110
blackened and nobody
wants to eat it.

00:09:55.110 --> 00:09:57.310
And that is the first pizza.

00:09:57.310 --> 00:09:59.430
Really, that bit.

00:09:59.430 --> 00:10:01.460
The word pizza itself is just a

00:10:01.460 --> 00:10:03.920
mispronunciation of the word pita.

00:10:03.920 --> 00:10:07.370
And pita goes back to the
ancient Aramaic word pitta,

00:10:07.370 --> 00:10:08.730
that just means bread.

00:10:08.730 --> 00:10:11.280
A pizza is really
just a bread.

00:10:11.280 --> 00:10:14.270
Pizza is not defined as crust,
sauce, and cheese.

00:10:14.270 --> 00:10:16.660
The tomato doesn't come
on until way later.

00:10:16.660 --> 00:10:20.450
Tomatoes, really the late 17th
century at the very earliest.

00:10:20.450 --> 00:10:23.150
Cheese is happening even later
than that, because cheese is

00:10:23.150 --> 00:10:25.160
just too expensive until
a certain point.

00:10:25.160 --> 00:10:28.200
It really is all about having
a flattened piece of dough,

00:10:28.200 --> 00:10:30.370
that when they start throwing
ingredients on top of it, the

00:10:30.370 --> 00:10:32.420
ingredients that they're adding
on top of that dough,

00:10:32.420 --> 00:10:35.260
it's also proximity, and
it's also economics.

00:10:35.260 --> 00:10:39.040
The butcher shop has leftover
pig fat, and that that's the

00:10:39.040 --> 00:10:40.550
first pizza topping--

00:10:40.550 --> 00:10:43.710
lard, just straight chunks of
lard thrown on top of a dough,

00:10:43.710 --> 00:10:44.920
and that's it.

00:10:44.920 --> 00:10:46.020
I don't think we
got any today.

00:10:46.020 --> 00:10:47.366
Did you order any lard?

00:10:47.366 --> 00:10:48.764
[LAUGHTER]

00:10:48.764 --> 00:10:50.340
SCOTT WIENER: And
I'm not kidding.

00:10:50.340 --> 00:10:52.120
There are places that do it.

00:10:52.120 --> 00:10:54.530
Keste on Bleecker Street and Don
Antonio, which is owned by

00:10:54.530 --> 00:10:56.570
the same guy, they
do that pizza.

00:10:56.570 --> 00:10:58.750
It's called the Mast'nicola,
and it's OK that

00:10:58.750 --> 00:10:58.950
you didn't get it.

00:10:58.950 --> 00:11:00.000
It's all right.

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:02.320
But if you ever have the
chance, try it out.

00:11:02.320 --> 00:11:02.740
Share it with people.

00:11:02.740 --> 00:11:05.360
You don't want to eat
that whole thing.

00:11:05.360 --> 00:11:06.860
And it's delicious.

00:11:06.860 --> 00:11:08.720
It's just a bunch of lard.

00:11:08.720 --> 00:11:11.790
But you end up having all these
ingredients back in the

00:11:11.790 --> 00:11:14.540
day that are just because
of proximity.

00:11:14.540 --> 00:11:16.450
So that's why when we're talking
about something like

00:11:16.450 --> 00:11:21.040
mashed potatoes at Bar in New
Haven, it's not like potatoes

00:11:21.040 --> 00:11:22.200
are hard to come by.

00:11:22.200 --> 00:11:23.450
Throw it on a pizza.

00:11:23.450 --> 00:11:25.680
If you're in a place that people
like eating Hawaiian

00:11:25.680 --> 00:11:27.970
pizza-- which is not
really popular in

00:11:27.970 --> 00:11:30.590
Hawaii, by the way--

00:11:30.590 --> 00:11:31.720
you've got pineapples handy?

00:11:31.720 --> 00:11:33.370
Why not, why the heck not?

00:11:33.370 --> 00:11:37.330
These ovens as a bread oven,
this is your starting point

00:11:37.330 --> 00:11:38.790
for all pizza.

00:11:38.790 --> 00:11:40.640
And throughout that,
we were starting to

00:11:40.640 --> 00:11:41.210
change a little bit.

00:11:41.210 --> 00:11:44.920
Like, when get onto the next
step in pizza ovens, when we

00:11:44.920 --> 00:11:48.700
get to John's, that John's pizza
is going come out of a

00:11:48.700 --> 00:11:51.490
massive coal-burning
brick oven.

00:11:51.490 --> 00:11:52.910
And this is a shot
of Lombardi's

00:11:52.910 --> 00:11:55.090
Pizzeria on Spring Street.

00:11:55.090 --> 00:11:58.110
Lombardi's is-- have any of you
guys been to Lombardi's?

00:11:58.110 --> 00:12:00.880
Yeah, Lombardi's right now
is at 32 Spring Street.

00:12:00.880 --> 00:12:04.140
This is a shot of the original
location, which is 53 and 1/2

00:12:04.140 --> 00:12:04.930
Spring Street.

00:12:04.930 --> 00:12:06.610
It's a bar called
Gatsby's now.

00:12:06.610 --> 00:12:10.360
And this oven is massive.

00:12:10.360 --> 00:12:11.990
You can see it's a wall.

00:12:11.990 --> 00:12:14.190
It's not like the little
standalone oven that we saw

00:12:14.190 --> 00:12:15.800
before with these little guys.

00:12:15.800 --> 00:12:19.140
This is a whole wall and it
extends about 12 feet into the

00:12:19.140 --> 00:12:20.590
backyard of this building.

00:12:20.590 --> 00:12:24.700
And again, proximity
and economics.

00:12:24.700 --> 00:12:27.980
We switched from wood to coal
just because wood is too

00:12:27.980 --> 00:12:30.680
expensive in Manhattan
in the late 1800s.

00:12:30.680 --> 00:12:33.340
In the late 1800s,
early 1900s, coal

00:12:33.340 --> 00:12:34.700
was just way cheaper.

00:12:34.700 --> 00:12:37.130
They were bringing in coal,
truckloads of coal, which were

00:12:37.130 --> 00:12:40.120
used for heating all of
downtown Manhattan.

00:12:40.120 --> 00:12:43.220
Anthracite coal was just cheap,
so that's what they

00:12:43.220 --> 00:12:46.010
used in this oven, which is why
that John's pizza that you

00:12:46.010 --> 00:12:48.390
have is a completely
different texture,

00:12:48.390 --> 00:12:49.960
completely different flavor.

00:12:49.960 --> 00:12:52.330
You're just getting
down to the crust.

00:12:52.330 --> 00:12:53.960
And this is sort of the
early version of

00:12:53.960 --> 00:12:57.580
New York style pizza.

00:12:57.580 --> 00:13:00.100
Even just from looking at it,
this pizza is larger than that

00:13:00.100 --> 00:13:02.900
Donatella pizza and it has a
little bit more to do with the

00:13:02.900 --> 00:13:05.570
ingredients that are available
here versus the ingredients

00:13:05.570 --> 00:13:09.080
that are available back in
southern Italy, in Naples.

00:13:09.080 --> 00:13:11.780
And then of course, the
final oven is the

00:13:11.780 --> 00:13:14.170
deck oven back here.

00:13:14.170 --> 00:13:16.910
And this is a shot of New York
Pizza Suprema, which we have

00:13:16.910 --> 00:13:18.180
smattered along over here.

00:13:18.180 --> 00:13:20.260
There's still a couple
of slices.

00:13:20.260 --> 00:13:23.630
And I had the opportunity of
working here for a short time,

00:13:23.630 --> 00:13:26.980
and I did grow that mustache
just so I would match

00:13:26.980 --> 00:13:30.000
everybody else who
worked there.

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:31.770
Everybody has a mustache
there.

00:13:31.770 --> 00:13:32.720
I wanted to fit in.

00:13:32.720 --> 00:13:34.670
I was writing a series of
articles called "Undercover

00:13:34.670 --> 00:13:37.610
Pizza Lover" for "Serious
Eats," and I did three

00:13:37.610 --> 00:13:38.310
different jobs.

00:13:38.310 --> 00:13:41.470
I worked as a slice slinger at
Suprema, I worked at a place

00:13:41.470 --> 00:13:43.640
called Metro Pizza in Las Vegas
where I was a pizza

00:13:43.640 --> 00:13:46.320
maker on a busy Saturday night,
and then I did three

00:13:46.320 --> 00:13:50.290
weeks at Domino's, where I went
totally undercover, I

00:13:50.290 --> 00:13:53.190
went rogue.

00:13:53.190 --> 00:13:55.260
I applied for the job and I
worked there for a bit and

00:13:55.260 --> 00:13:58.280
learned so much about why I
don't ever want to go near

00:13:58.280 --> 00:14:00.100
there again.

00:14:00.100 --> 00:14:02.160
But anyway, I just wanted
to show you guys.

00:14:02.160 --> 00:14:04.640
Obviously, you all know this
oven probably better than

00:14:04.640 --> 00:14:06.900
anything else, but there's a
lot of interesting things

00:14:06.900 --> 00:14:08.150
about this type of oven.

00:14:08.150 --> 00:14:10.740
And that oven, in fact,
is part of why we

00:14:10.740 --> 00:14:12.080
even are here today.

00:14:12.080 --> 00:14:16.850
We would not be here today if
pizza stopped with this.

00:14:16.850 --> 00:14:19.590
If they switched over to a
coal-burning oven and suddenly

00:14:19.590 --> 00:14:21.860
everyone was like, oh, no I'm
not interested anymore--

00:14:21.860 --> 00:14:22.610
done.

00:14:22.610 --> 00:14:26.550
You see, it's all about fuel
sources becoming cheaper.

00:14:26.550 --> 00:14:27.870
The fuel source for--

00:14:27.870 --> 00:14:28.770
I mean, coal.

00:14:28.770 --> 00:14:31.440
In the late 1930s, coal
becomes too expensive.

00:14:31.440 --> 00:14:35.570
Natural gas starts to be the big
seller, and so natural gas

00:14:35.570 --> 00:14:38.030
is great for an oven like this
because you can just flip a

00:14:38.030 --> 00:14:40.990
switch and it's on, flip
a switch and it's off.

00:14:40.990 --> 00:14:43.110
Lombardi's, you can't do that.

00:14:43.110 --> 00:14:46.220
At John's, you can't do that.

00:14:46.220 --> 00:14:48.510
At Totonno's in Coney Island
or Patsy's in Harlem, you

00:14:48.510 --> 00:14:49.430
can't do that.

00:14:49.430 --> 00:14:52.110
The switch that you have
to flick doesn't exist.

00:14:52.110 --> 00:14:54.350
Instead, to turn the oven off,
you've got to scoop out the

00:14:54.350 --> 00:14:59.180
coal and then you've got to pull
it out of the oven, and

00:14:59.180 --> 00:15:01.860
then you have to wait two
days or three days.

00:15:01.860 --> 00:15:02.890
Really, I'm not kidding.

00:15:02.890 --> 00:15:05.090
You have to wait two or three
days, and then if you want to

00:15:05.090 --> 00:15:07.920
heat it back up-- let's say your
coal oven goes down to

00:15:07.920 --> 00:15:11.480
room temp, you're talking two
and a half weeks, just because

00:15:11.480 --> 00:15:13.550
it's all about the masonry
of the oven.

00:15:13.550 --> 00:15:15.900
So that's why sometimes
pizzerias tell you about how

00:15:15.900 --> 00:15:17.310
hot their ovens are.

00:15:17.310 --> 00:15:20.200
The heat in the air of the oven
doesn't make as much of a

00:15:20.200 --> 00:15:21.260
difference as the masonry.

00:15:21.260 --> 00:15:21.731
What's up?

00:15:21.731 --> 00:15:26.770
AUDIENCE: So those coal ovens,
they run continuously?

00:15:26.770 --> 00:15:28.482
Patsy's and Luzzo's?

00:15:28.482 --> 00:15:31.290
SCOTT WIENER: Yes, they
run continuously.

00:15:31.290 --> 00:15:33.060
Luzzo's is an interesting
one because they

00:15:33.060 --> 00:15:34.900
don't use solely coal.

00:15:34.900 --> 00:15:37.680
They use coal and they put
wood on top of it.

00:15:37.680 --> 00:15:38.800
So that's a coal-burning oven.

00:15:38.800 --> 00:15:40.700
It's built as a coal-burning
oven, but they also do

00:15:40.700 --> 00:15:41.440
wood on top of it.

00:15:41.440 --> 00:15:43.690
And they're hot all the time.

00:15:43.690 --> 00:15:45.565
Places like Lombardi's
have a bigger oven.

00:15:45.565 --> 00:15:47.950
It's physically bigger, so
that's why they keep it going

00:15:47.950 --> 00:15:51.200
all the time because it's more
efficient to let it go all

00:15:51.200 --> 00:15:53.400
night than it would be to start
the fire in the morning

00:15:53.400 --> 00:15:55.220
and then try to reheat
it for three hours.

00:15:55.220 --> 00:15:57.670
It's just more of a struggle,
it's harder, so it's easier

00:15:57.670 --> 00:15:59.270
for them to maintain
it like that.

00:15:59.270 --> 00:16:02.290
And each oven has these
different nuances to it, which

00:16:02.290 --> 00:16:03.560
are so fascinating.

00:16:03.560 --> 00:16:05.160
The way that they work
is so fascinating.

00:16:05.160 --> 00:16:08.260
The inside of a wood-burning
oven, first of all, it just

00:16:08.260 --> 00:16:10.120
looks great.

00:16:10.120 --> 00:16:11.550
This is why people--

00:16:11.550 --> 00:16:13.300
I don't know if you know it,
but a lot of people are

00:16:13.300 --> 00:16:16.900
installing ovens in
their backyards.

00:16:16.900 --> 00:16:17.770
Not in Brooklyn as much.

00:16:17.770 --> 00:16:20.850
But if anybody's interested in
doing that, please talk to me.

00:16:20.850 --> 00:16:22.900
Seriously, I'm not kidding.

00:16:22.900 --> 00:16:24.900
I looked at this apartment a
couple weeks ago and they were

00:16:24.900 --> 00:16:27.450
telling me, we're going to do
some projects in the backyard

00:16:27.450 --> 00:16:30.110
and thinking about putting in
a wood-burning oven, and I

00:16:30.110 --> 00:16:30.840
freaked out.

00:16:30.840 --> 00:16:33.360
And that's probably why I didn't
get the place, because

00:16:33.360 --> 00:16:34.580
I was so excited about it.

00:16:34.580 --> 00:16:36.360
But I went over there a week
later and I was like, here's

00:16:36.360 --> 00:16:38.750
some books.

00:16:38.750 --> 00:16:39.590
Just invite me over.

00:16:39.590 --> 00:16:41.360
But you notice it's a
dome shape in the

00:16:41.360 --> 00:16:43.530
inside of the oven.

00:16:43.530 --> 00:16:46.750
This dome shape is really good
because it's going to help

00:16:46.750 --> 00:16:49.060
heat transmit by all three
methods of heat

00:16:49.060 --> 00:16:50.440
transfer in an oven.

00:16:50.440 --> 00:16:52.030
Direct conduction--

00:16:52.030 --> 00:16:54.570
the pizza's laying directly
on the floor of the oven.

00:16:54.570 --> 00:16:57.170
There's heat conducting right
from the floor into the base

00:16:57.170 --> 00:16:57.840
of the pizza.

00:16:57.840 --> 00:17:00.810
You're going to have a lot of
radiation, because all the

00:17:00.810 --> 00:17:04.480
heat that's bouncing off those
bricks on the top is going to

00:17:04.480 --> 00:17:06.460
centralize back on the
floor of the oven.

00:17:06.460 --> 00:17:09.099
And then of course, you
have convection.

00:17:09.099 --> 00:17:11.210
Since this fire-- you notice
how the fire is

00:17:11.210 --> 00:17:13.369
sort of to the left?

00:17:13.369 --> 00:17:15.865
I'm taking the picture through
the only opening in that oven.

00:17:15.865 --> 00:17:18.270
It's one opening, right
in the front.

00:17:18.270 --> 00:17:21.750
So air can only get in or out
through that one opening.

00:17:21.750 --> 00:17:26.380
I know in the picture I showed
you before, there were these

00:17:26.380 --> 00:17:28.590
vents up on top, the flue.

00:17:28.590 --> 00:17:32.510
Each of those flues is not
connected directly to the peak

00:17:32.510 --> 00:17:34.430
of the dome of the oven.

00:17:34.430 --> 00:17:39.180
All cool air to feed the logs
is going right in along the

00:17:39.180 --> 00:17:43.370
bottom, hitting the fire,
heating up, swirling around,

00:17:43.370 --> 00:17:47.660
and coming out the front
and up into the hood.

00:17:47.660 --> 00:17:51.160
So that hood is connected to
that flue in the back.

00:17:51.160 --> 00:17:53.500
That's why when you look inside
this oven, there's no

00:17:53.500 --> 00:17:54.740
opening inside there.

00:17:54.740 --> 00:17:56.470
All that heat is coming
right out the front.

00:17:56.470 --> 00:18:00.770
But again, the problem is these
ovens don't really work

00:18:00.770 --> 00:18:03.080
as well when you come into New
York City, just because of the

00:18:03.080 --> 00:18:06.400
expense of the fuel, which is
why we're going to change

00:18:06.400 --> 00:18:07.110
things up a little bit.

00:18:07.110 --> 00:18:09.850
But I just wanted to show you
another quick image about how

00:18:09.850 --> 00:18:14.470
fresh air is going to come in
the front, warm up, move out,

00:18:14.470 --> 00:18:17.430
and exit again out the front.

00:18:17.430 --> 00:18:20.760
But a coal-burning oven
is different.

00:18:20.760 --> 00:18:23.240
This is a more recent photo.

00:18:23.240 --> 00:18:25.490
This is a place called
Verde in Bushwick.

00:18:25.490 --> 00:18:26.790
I think it's on Irving.

00:18:26.790 --> 00:18:30.330
And this is an oven that the
guy bought the building, he

00:18:30.330 --> 00:18:33.040
was messing around, and found
that, hey, this is not the

00:18:33.040 --> 00:18:35.660
wall, this is an oven.

00:18:35.660 --> 00:18:37.310
And why not?

00:18:37.310 --> 00:18:38.280
This is the way it works.

00:18:38.280 --> 00:18:41.490
You see, these ovens at a place
like Lombardi's or at

00:18:41.490 --> 00:18:44.690
similar places-- actually, in
New Haven at Pepe's and at

00:18:44.690 --> 00:18:47.330
Sally's, if you look at the
profile of any of these

00:18:47.330 --> 00:18:49.950
buildings that have these old
coal-burning ovens, the

00:18:49.950 --> 00:18:53.440
building is three or four
stories tall and then it drops

00:18:53.440 --> 00:18:57.390
down to a one-story extension
for, 20, 30, 40 feet, and then

00:18:57.390 --> 00:18:59.050
there's a chimney at the end.

00:18:59.050 --> 00:19:01.420
And that extension
is the oven.

00:19:01.420 --> 00:19:03.310
It's all the oven, if you
look at the profile.

00:19:03.310 --> 00:19:04.550
This one is interesting,
though.

00:19:04.550 --> 00:19:06.410
This one's not on the
ground floor.

00:19:06.410 --> 00:19:09.290
This one is in the ground.

00:19:09.290 --> 00:19:11.140
It's underneath the sidewalk.

00:19:11.140 --> 00:19:13.390
So this oven extends in the
front of the building

00:19:13.390 --> 00:19:15.870
underneath the sidewalk,
almost definitely built

00:19:15.870 --> 00:19:18.250
illegally about 100,
110 years ago.

00:19:18.250 --> 00:19:19.720
That's the way that
they rolled.

00:19:19.720 --> 00:19:22.390
They just built something and
they said, if I get busted,

00:19:22.390 --> 00:19:24.160
I'll get the permit later.

00:19:24.160 --> 00:19:25.460
And that's what happened.

00:19:25.460 --> 00:19:27.960
I found the permit for
Lombardi's, the Lombardi's

00:19:27.960 --> 00:19:30.940
oven for 1898.

00:19:30.940 --> 00:19:34.430
But that oven is probably a
little bit older than that.

00:19:34.430 --> 00:19:36.540
If they got the permit in 1898,
I don't think they were

00:19:36.540 --> 00:19:39.070
like, let's get all of our ducks
in a row and make sure

00:19:39.070 --> 00:19:40.210
everything's right.

00:19:40.210 --> 00:19:42.450
We just moved here three years
ago, we know the rules.

00:19:42.450 --> 00:19:43.900
No, it was just they just
did it and they

00:19:43.900 --> 00:19:45.280
figured it out later.

00:19:45.280 --> 00:19:47.060
The way this works is
totally different.

00:19:47.060 --> 00:19:50.680
Instead of having one opening in
the front, it's got three.

00:19:50.680 --> 00:19:52.030
And this is just a handle.

00:19:52.030 --> 00:19:53.030
There's a light switch
back there.

00:19:53.030 --> 00:19:53.830
That's not an opening.

00:19:53.830 --> 00:19:56.420
There's an opening right here,
and then that little doorway

00:19:56.420 --> 00:19:58.670
to the right, and then
below that doorway.

00:19:58.670 --> 00:20:01.910
So inside that door, that little
slightly curved, little

00:20:01.910 --> 00:20:04.500
adorable little elf door,
that's where they

00:20:04.500 --> 00:20:06.150
shovel the coal in.

00:20:06.150 --> 00:20:08.740
Right below it is the ash drop,
which sometimes they'll

00:20:08.740 --> 00:20:11.460
leave open so that air
can flow in, air

00:20:11.460 --> 00:20:12.670
can feed the fire.

00:20:12.670 --> 00:20:16.190
And as that air goes up through
the fire, heats up,

00:20:16.190 --> 00:20:18.540
hits the top of the oven right
around here, it's going to

00:20:18.540 --> 00:20:21.520
flow all the way to the back
left corner to exit out the

00:20:21.520 --> 00:20:22.810
flue in this oven.

00:20:22.810 --> 00:20:25.350
So instead of being a circular
motion in the inside of the

00:20:25.350 --> 00:20:27.640
oven, it's going straight
across.

00:20:27.640 --> 00:20:29.530
And that heat, as it goes
straight across, is a

00:20:29.530 --> 00:20:31.960
completely different bake
when we go from

00:20:31.960 --> 00:20:33.660
Donatella to John's.

00:20:33.660 --> 00:20:37.680
You notice Donatella's pizza,
it's a lot softer, it's a

00:20:37.680 --> 00:20:39.940
little more consistent
in texture.

00:20:39.940 --> 00:20:44.420
John's pizza tends to be a
little tougher, a little bit

00:20:44.420 --> 00:20:46.900
more of a bite, and that's
because the bake time is going

00:20:46.900 --> 00:20:47.900
to be longer.

00:20:47.900 --> 00:20:51.830
Donatella's pizza comes out in
60 to 90 seconds, and John's

00:20:51.830 --> 00:20:53.800
is five minutes-- not that
five minutes is bad.

00:20:53.800 --> 00:20:55.776
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
pizza, [INAUDIBLE].

00:21:01.392 --> 00:21:03.450
SCOTT WIENER: You know,
it's interesting.

00:21:03.450 --> 00:21:07.740
Anthracite is about 92%, 93%
carbon content, so there's not

00:21:07.740 --> 00:21:08.630
a lot of moisture.

00:21:08.630 --> 00:21:11.310
Burning wood lets off a lot more
smoke than burning coal,

00:21:11.310 --> 00:21:12.370
a lot more smoke.

00:21:12.370 --> 00:21:14.795
The difference is that the ash
is easier to get rid of from a

00:21:14.795 --> 00:21:17.110
wood oven than it is from
a coal oven, so

00:21:17.110 --> 00:21:17.840
that's the big thing.

00:21:17.840 --> 00:21:19.930
And of course, burning a fossil
fuel is not a great

00:21:19.930 --> 00:21:24.040
deal, so I would not, by any
means, advocate coal-fired

00:21:24.040 --> 00:21:27.310
pizzerias happening in every
city around the world.

00:21:27.310 --> 00:21:28.610
But it's not as harmful.

00:21:28.610 --> 00:21:30.940
People think it's going to be
harmful because coal has this

00:21:30.940 --> 00:21:33.130
bad rep, as it probably
should be.

00:21:33.130 --> 00:21:34.890
But it's not.

00:21:34.890 --> 00:21:37.460
It's really any of the coal, any
of the heat, is coming on

00:21:37.460 --> 00:21:38.580
the right side of the oven.

00:21:38.580 --> 00:21:41.800
No pizzas are baking on the
right side of the oven.

00:21:41.800 --> 00:21:42.780
They're all baking
on the left.

00:21:42.780 --> 00:21:44.000
And they can't bake on
the right, because

00:21:44.000 --> 00:21:45.630
it's just too hot.

00:21:45.630 --> 00:21:48.590
And that coal fire is also a
different fire from wood.

00:21:48.590 --> 00:21:50.570
It's more smoldering.

00:21:50.570 --> 00:21:52.760
You don't have huge flames
leaping about.

00:21:52.760 --> 00:21:54.950
With that wood-fired oven,
you've got flames that go up

00:21:54.950 --> 00:21:57.910
to 12 o'clock on the top of that
dome, and that flame is

00:21:57.910 --> 00:22:01.920
going to help you get blisters
on the edge of your crust.

00:22:01.920 --> 00:22:04.190
It's not that they chose, oh,
let's make the flame big to

00:22:04.190 --> 00:22:05.030
get blisters.

00:22:05.030 --> 00:22:08.090
It was more like, oh, we threw
the dough in when the oven is

00:22:08.090 --> 00:22:10.980
really hot and the flame is
reaching up to the top, and we

00:22:10.980 --> 00:22:12.230
end up getting these blisters.

00:22:12.230 --> 00:22:15.020
And then the people of Naples
figure oh, well, we can't

00:22:15.020 --> 00:22:16.840
change anything, because
we like it.

00:22:16.840 --> 00:22:19.480
So that's why today we have
an organization called the

00:22:19.480 --> 00:22:22.780
Associaziane Verace Pizza
Napoletana, or the pizza

00:22:22.780 --> 00:22:24.890
police, as some people
call them.

00:22:24.890 --> 00:22:27.860
And they have a series of rules
that say the pizza must

00:22:27.860 --> 00:22:31.160
be 35 centimeters in diameter,
the tomato that you use on top

00:22:31.160 --> 00:22:34.040
of it must be San Marzano, and
it must be applied to the

00:22:34.040 --> 00:22:36.370
dough in a circular motion.

00:22:36.370 --> 00:22:38.240
And I'm not kidding
about that.

00:22:38.240 --> 00:22:40.810
And it says the oil must be
extra virgin, and the cheese

00:22:40.810 --> 00:22:43.060
must be fresh fior di latte,
which is a cow's milk

00:22:43.060 --> 00:22:45.460
mozzarella, or buffalo
milk mozzarella.

00:22:45.460 --> 00:22:46.850
They don't give you
any leeway.

00:22:46.850 --> 00:22:49.500
It's really funny to me because
so many pizzerias, you

00:22:49.500 --> 00:22:52.600
think that, like, oh, they've
got secret recipes.

00:22:52.600 --> 00:22:53.850
Secrets.

00:22:53.850 --> 00:22:54.600
No secrets.

00:22:54.600 --> 00:22:58.290
In fact, they publish what
you have to do to

00:22:58.290 --> 00:23:00.440
make the right pizza.

00:23:00.440 --> 00:23:03.340
The best pizza has no secrets,
because the best pizza is

00:23:03.340 --> 00:23:06.180
really pretty simple for me,
at least what I like.

00:23:06.180 --> 00:23:09.700
But this type of oven, again,
completely different from what

00:23:09.700 --> 00:23:10.930
we saw before.

00:23:10.930 --> 00:23:13.660
So that's why it's so hard to
pick out what is the best,

00:23:13.660 --> 00:23:16.200
because the oven's just going
to bake things differently.

00:23:16.200 --> 00:23:18.520
It's more like you've got to
pick what you're into.

00:23:18.520 --> 00:23:20.600
You've got to pick if you're
into basketball

00:23:20.600 --> 00:23:21.720
or football or baseball.

00:23:21.720 --> 00:23:24.230
They're all different paces of
sport, they're all different.

00:23:24.230 --> 00:23:26.710
So that's why with these ovens,
you kind of have to

00:23:26.710 --> 00:23:28.860
know which type of oven your
pizza's coming from.

00:23:28.860 --> 00:23:31.730
And of course, there could be
wood-fired ovens that the

00:23:31.730 --> 00:23:35.060
pizza comes out tasting
and looking like a

00:23:35.060 --> 00:23:36.510
gas-fueled deck oven.

00:23:36.510 --> 00:23:38.880
That just means that it's not
being used the way it's

00:23:38.880 --> 00:23:42.160
intended to, and that's all
in the hands of the user.

00:23:42.160 --> 00:23:43.790
These are just tools.

00:23:43.790 --> 00:23:45.560
Just because you have a
coal-burning oven or a

00:23:45.560 --> 00:23:47.860
wood-burning oven in your
backyard does not mean that

00:23:47.860 --> 00:23:50.790
you're making the right
type of pizza.

00:23:50.790 --> 00:23:53.650
So with this kind of oven, the
inside of it-- and this is

00:23:53.650 --> 00:23:54.230
actually funny.

00:23:54.230 --> 00:23:57.590
This is a rare day when at the
very beginning of the day,

00:23:57.590 --> 00:23:59.950
when they still have wood in the
pile to help burn some of

00:23:59.950 --> 00:24:01.980
the coals, where you
do have a flame.

00:24:01.980 --> 00:24:05.100
But that flame is not by any
means reaching as far as the

00:24:05.100 --> 00:24:05.880
flame before.

00:24:05.880 --> 00:24:08.920
This is a picture I took of the
inside of Lombardi's oven

00:24:08.920 --> 00:24:12.100
after they did a huge
restoration job to it to make

00:24:12.100 --> 00:24:14.540
it look the way it used
to look, the inside.

00:24:14.540 --> 00:24:16.860
And you see the way the
inside is shaped.

00:24:16.860 --> 00:24:18.200
It's like a barrel vault.

00:24:18.200 --> 00:24:20.870
It's not a dome, so heat
is moving from

00:24:20.870 --> 00:24:22.240
one side to the other.

00:24:22.240 --> 00:24:24.500
It is not moving in a
circular motion--

00:24:24.500 --> 00:24:25.760
one side to the other.

00:24:25.760 --> 00:24:27.980
And you're not going to have
any pizza over there.

00:24:27.980 --> 00:24:29.700
Pizzas are going to start
right around that

00:24:29.700 --> 00:24:31.900
point in the center.

00:24:31.900 --> 00:24:33.930
And if they have calzones,
they're going to be baked

00:24:33.930 --> 00:24:36.670
closer to the front door,
because it's colder by the

00:24:36.670 --> 00:24:37.150
front door.

00:24:37.150 --> 00:24:38.750
Calzones are thick.

00:24:38.750 --> 00:24:39.980
You don't want to bake
it very quickly.

00:24:39.980 --> 00:24:43.940
You want to bake it at a nice
pace, an even pace, so that

00:24:43.940 --> 00:24:45.720
the outside can bake and
the inside can bake.

00:24:45.720 --> 00:24:46.880
But they're just fascinating.

00:24:46.880 --> 00:24:49.030
They're just a real pain.

00:24:49.030 --> 00:24:51.060
Nobody wants to use these ovens
anymore, and that's why

00:24:51.060 --> 00:24:55.630
they fell out of vogue, also
because to maintain them--

00:24:55.630 --> 00:24:57.840
you've got the coal on
the side of it--

00:24:57.840 --> 00:25:00.170
every morning and every
afternoon, in the middle of

00:25:00.170 --> 00:25:02.380
the afternoon before the dinner
rush happens, you've

00:25:02.380 --> 00:25:05.490
got to scrape out
the excess coal.

00:25:05.490 --> 00:25:08.290
So you can see better in this
photograph, that little open

00:25:08.290 --> 00:25:09.380
door on the bottom.

00:25:09.380 --> 00:25:12.685
That's air coming straight in to
fuel the coal, and the coal

00:25:12.685 --> 00:25:15.200
is sitting on top of
a metal grate just

00:25:15.200 --> 00:25:16.450
so you can get airflow.

00:25:19.010 --> 00:25:24.030
Oh, these are my feet, sticking
out of the oven.

00:25:24.030 --> 00:25:26.600
I wanted to show you this,
because when I told you about

00:25:26.600 --> 00:25:29.550
waiting two or three days to
repair the oven, I'm serious.

00:25:29.550 --> 00:25:32.430
This was two, two and a
half days after they

00:25:32.430 --> 00:25:33.580
shut down the oven.

00:25:33.580 --> 00:25:36.320
And they were sending people in
to replace broken bricks.

00:25:36.320 --> 00:25:38.960
This is a picture I took right
before they did that huge

00:25:38.960 --> 00:25:41.830
restoration for the inside, and
they let me crawl in there

00:25:41.830 --> 00:25:44.080
for 10 seconds, and
it was amazing.

00:25:44.080 --> 00:25:45.290
And I never want to do it
again, because it was

00:25:45.290 --> 00:25:46.050
terrifying.

00:25:46.050 --> 00:25:50.130
But the inside of the
oven, it's so hot.

00:25:50.130 --> 00:25:53.900
It was 322 degrees Fahrenheit at
that moment that the photo

00:25:53.900 --> 00:25:55.750
was taken on the floor
of the oven.

00:25:55.750 --> 00:25:58.800
Luckily, I'm sitting on a piece
of plywood, so that's

00:25:58.800 --> 00:26:00.110
why I'm OK.

00:26:00.110 --> 00:26:03.300
But it's extraordinarily hot.

00:26:03.300 --> 00:26:05.720
Again, that's why who in their
right mind would want to build

00:26:05.720 --> 00:26:09.310
one of these now when
you have to do this?

00:26:09.310 --> 00:26:12.510
Have any of you guys heard about
why there aren't so many

00:26:12.510 --> 00:26:14.420
coal ovens around anymore?

00:26:14.420 --> 00:26:16.260
A lot of people ask me about--

00:26:16.260 --> 00:26:19.370
they hear that it's illegal to
build a coal-burning oven, for

00:26:19.370 --> 00:26:21.260
environmental reasons
or for whatever.

00:26:21.260 --> 00:26:22.350
It's not at all.

00:26:22.350 --> 00:26:24.400
It's 100% legal.

00:26:24.400 --> 00:26:25.970
It's just nobody would do
it, because that's how

00:26:25.970 --> 00:26:27.160
you have to fix it.

00:26:27.160 --> 00:26:30.320
So rather than do that, it's
easier to just get one of

00:26:30.320 --> 00:26:33.560
these ovens, to get one of these
gas-fueled deck ovens.

00:26:33.560 --> 00:26:34.510
How many of you have
been here?

00:26:34.510 --> 00:26:35.310
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:26:35.310 --> 00:26:36.860
SCOTT WIENER: Yeah.

00:26:36.860 --> 00:26:38.650
That's why I put this picture
in here, because I knew that

00:26:38.650 --> 00:26:40.020
it would send a bolt
of electricity

00:26:40.020 --> 00:26:42.220
through your hearts.

00:26:42.220 --> 00:26:44.870
And for anybody who has not been
there, this is a place

00:26:44.870 --> 00:26:45.940
that you will go.

00:26:45.940 --> 00:26:46.590
It's OK.

00:26:46.590 --> 00:26:48.000
Don't go with too many people.

00:26:48.000 --> 00:26:49.880
Go at 11:30 on a Wednesday.

00:26:49.880 --> 00:26:51.630
Call in sick to work.

00:26:51.630 --> 00:26:53.920
I didn't say that out loud.

00:26:53.920 --> 00:26:56.060
It's just, he's the only
guy who makes the

00:26:56.060 --> 00:26:57.220
pizza at this place.

00:26:57.220 --> 00:26:57.840
This is Dom DeMarco.

00:26:57.840 --> 00:27:00.530
He's at a place called
the Di Fara on Avenue

00:27:00.530 --> 00:27:03.790
J in Midwood, Brooklyn.

00:27:03.790 --> 00:27:05.870
This is actually a rare picture,
because he's using

00:27:05.870 --> 00:27:08.460
the a peel to take the
pizza, the Sicilian

00:27:08.460 --> 00:27:09.380
pizza, out of the oven.

00:27:09.380 --> 00:27:12.820
Usually he just grabs it, which
is also terrifying,

00:27:12.820 --> 00:27:14.050
because it's super hot.

00:27:14.050 --> 00:27:15.610
But these are deck ovens.

00:27:15.610 --> 00:27:18.000
And a lot of times people look
at that and they're like, oh,

00:27:18.000 --> 00:27:20.030
no, I like brick oven pizza.

00:27:20.030 --> 00:27:22.840
Meanwhile, this guy makes some
of the best pizza in the city.

00:27:22.840 --> 00:27:26.380
And regardless of whatever lists
in the Zagat survey and

00:27:26.380 --> 00:27:28.930
all that, most people--

00:27:28.930 --> 00:27:31.230
my bus guy this morning
is telling me

00:27:31.230 --> 00:27:32.830
about, you're crazy.

00:27:32.830 --> 00:27:35.080
You like the Sicilian here
better than Di Fara.

00:27:35.080 --> 00:27:35.640
Whatever.

00:27:35.640 --> 00:27:37.060
I wanted to show you
this, because he's

00:27:37.060 --> 00:27:39.140
using these deck ovens.

00:27:39.140 --> 00:27:42.470
He's using an oven that is the
cheapest oven, and yet an oven

00:27:42.470 --> 00:27:44.530
that started to proliferate
right after the Second World

00:27:44.530 --> 00:27:47.270
War, after you've got a lot of
American soldiers coming back

00:27:47.270 --> 00:27:49.020
from serving in Italy
during the war.

00:27:49.020 --> 00:27:51.620
And they're coming back and
saying, well, I'm not going to

00:27:51.620 --> 00:27:55.390
build a giant oven, because of
the expense and what if I go

00:27:55.390 --> 00:27:57.350
out of business, what if
I don't do anything?

00:27:57.350 --> 00:27:59.420
You get one of these
ovens in 1954.

00:27:59.420 --> 00:28:02.200
One of those ovens-- and there
are three in this picture.

00:28:02.200 --> 00:28:04.630
One of those ovens was
going for $500 new,

00:28:04.630 --> 00:28:07.100
$250 used on the Bowery.

00:28:07.100 --> 00:28:10.180
You could have bought any one of
these ovens for $250 used.

00:28:10.180 --> 00:28:11.900
So you could put that
in your place.

00:28:11.900 --> 00:28:14.530
If you go out of business, put
a For Sale sign on it, and

00:28:14.530 --> 00:28:15.250
then you're done.

00:28:15.250 --> 00:28:18.340
If you have these coal-burning
brick ovens, and you go out of

00:28:18.340 --> 00:28:20.350
business, you walk
away from it.

00:28:20.350 --> 00:28:22.730
A lot of times you put up
a wall in front of it.

00:28:22.730 --> 00:28:24.100
There are so many of
those coal ovens

00:28:24.100 --> 00:28:25.340
laying around the city.

00:28:25.340 --> 00:28:26.270
So many.

00:28:26.270 --> 00:28:28.580
And you put up a wall in front
of it and walk away and

00:28:28.580 --> 00:28:29.870
pretend it's not there.

00:28:29.870 --> 00:28:32.350
And that happened to my
friend David Sheridan.

00:28:32.350 --> 00:28:36.910
David is opening up a place on
Church Avenue in Ditmas Park

00:28:36.910 --> 00:28:39.440
in, I guess, a couple
of months.

00:28:39.440 --> 00:28:40.660
He signed a lease
on this place.

00:28:40.660 --> 00:28:41.980
A week later, went
in and tried to

00:28:41.980 --> 00:28:43.570
clean up the basement.

00:28:43.570 --> 00:28:45.335
And he finds this coal-burning
oven.

00:28:45.335 --> 00:28:46.680
He's opening a pizzeria there.

00:28:46.680 --> 00:28:48.630
He got an electric oven to use,
because he's like, well,

00:28:48.630 --> 00:28:50.530
I don't want to deal with the
hassle of anything else.

00:28:50.530 --> 00:28:51.710
And there it is.

00:28:51.710 --> 00:28:53.590
Right there, a coal-burning
oven sitting there.

00:28:53.590 --> 00:28:54.830
It's absolutely incredible.

00:28:54.830 --> 00:28:57.170
The current Lombardi's
oven is not the

00:28:57.170 --> 00:28:58.100
original Lombardi's oven.

00:28:58.100 --> 00:29:01.990
The original Lombardi's oven
broke because the Six Train

00:29:01.990 --> 00:29:03.560
runs directly underneath it.

00:29:03.560 --> 00:29:06.050
So when they moved to their
current location, they moved

00:29:06.050 --> 00:29:08.640
there because it's an old bakery
oven that was used in a

00:29:08.640 --> 00:29:10.220
place called the
Parisi Bakery.

00:29:10.220 --> 00:29:12.140
And when Parisi went out of
business in the late '70s,

00:29:12.140 --> 00:29:14.450
they put up a wall in front
of it, walked away.

00:29:14.450 --> 00:29:16.320
They said, we don't need
to do demolition.

00:29:16.320 --> 00:29:17.570
Nobody will know.

00:29:17.570 --> 00:29:18.800
Lombardi's knew.

00:29:18.800 --> 00:29:21.310
And when they went out of
business, they came in and

00:29:21.310 --> 00:29:23.130
they're said, well, we're
going to take this.

00:29:23.130 --> 00:29:24.340
It's perfect, you know?

00:29:24.340 --> 00:29:26.800
It's like when you see, oh, this
house already has a pool

00:29:26.800 --> 00:29:27.860
in the backyard.

00:29:27.860 --> 00:29:28.540
Let's get it.

00:29:28.540 --> 00:29:29.800
You know?

00:29:29.800 --> 00:29:32.390
That coal-burning oven is the
pool in the backyard of the

00:29:32.390 --> 00:29:33.540
pizzeria's house.

00:29:33.540 --> 00:29:34.450
What?

00:29:34.450 --> 00:29:38.070
So that's why it's interesting
that we get to these ovens.

00:29:38.070 --> 00:29:40.480
And this is really what
people were using

00:29:40.480 --> 00:29:41.790
because it made sense.

00:29:41.790 --> 00:29:44.210
Of course it works totally
differently.

00:29:44.210 --> 00:29:48.560
The bottom door on any of these
ovens, that's called the

00:29:48.560 --> 00:29:49.490
service door.

00:29:49.490 --> 00:29:52.950
You have two pipes underneath
that have a natural gas-fueled

00:29:52.950 --> 00:29:55.600
flame that's heating
up the stone.

00:29:55.600 --> 00:29:57.990
But on the top of the oven and
on the sides and on the back,

00:29:57.990 --> 00:29:59.180
it's all stainless.

00:29:59.180 --> 00:30:03.440
So it's not really good at
radiating a lot of heat.

00:30:03.440 --> 00:30:05.410
It's not going to bake
a lot from the top.

00:30:05.410 --> 00:30:07.140
It's going to bake mostly
from the bottom.

00:30:07.140 --> 00:30:10.220
And that's why the pizzas from
Suprema are baked differently

00:30:10.220 --> 00:30:13.120
from the pizzas from John's
and from Donatella.

00:30:13.120 --> 00:30:15.010
John's has more char going on.

00:30:15.010 --> 00:30:16.600
Donatella's lighter
and fluffier.

00:30:16.600 --> 00:30:19.890
Suprema is that classic New York
slice, that you can pick

00:30:19.890 --> 00:30:21.680
it up and fold it.

00:30:21.680 --> 00:30:24.650
And the cheese only starts
to move a little bit.

00:30:24.650 --> 00:30:26.680
It starts to migrate
toward the bottom.

00:30:26.680 --> 00:30:29.200
And the oil starts to gather,
and you could drip a little

00:30:29.200 --> 00:30:29.880
bit off the front.

00:30:29.880 --> 00:30:32.040
But don't blot it, at
least not in front

00:30:32.040 --> 00:30:33.170
of people you respect.

00:30:33.170 --> 00:30:36.550
And then you pick it up and it
doesn't crack on the bottom.

00:30:36.550 --> 00:30:37.060
You take a bite.

00:30:37.060 --> 00:30:38.590
It's pure bliss.

00:30:38.590 --> 00:30:39.900
But that's the slice.

00:30:39.900 --> 00:30:43.020
It's so far removed from the
origin, and people get into

00:30:43.020 --> 00:30:44.860
arguments all the time.

00:30:44.860 --> 00:30:45.910
Southern Italians especially.

00:30:45.910 --> 00:30:47.560
Oh, that's not pizza.

00:30:47.560 --> 00:30:50.060
Meanwhile, in southern Italy,
they're eating pizza with

00:30:50.060 --> 00:30:52.230
French fries and hot dogs
on it, and they're

00:30:52.230 --> 00:30:53.480
saying that that's OK.

00:30:53.480 --> 00:30:54.220
It's not OK.

00:30:54.220 --> 00:30:55.645
You know?

00:30:55.645 --> 00:30:57.490
And if that's OK, then
all this is OK.

00:30:57.490 --> 00:30:59.980
Which I personally believe
that it's all OK.

00:30:59.980 --> 00:31:02.450
And that's why it's so
interesting that, in an oven

00:31:02.450 --> 00:31:03.940
like this, it's a tool.

00:31:03.940 --> 00:31:05.600
This guy makes these pizzas.

00:31:05.600 --> 00:31:09.520
And I take people from Naples
to this pizzeria sometimes.

00:31:09.520 --> 00:31:10.390
And they're into it.

00:31:10.390 --> 00:31:12.495
I'm like, just don't
worry, and they're

00:31:12.495 --> 00:31:14.890
like, oh, it's small.

00:31:14.890 --> 00:31:16.020
And then they go in and
they eat it, and

00:31:16.020 --> 00:31:16.720
they understand it.

00:31:16.720 --> 00:31:17.730
And then they start
talking to him.

00:31:17.730 --> 00:31:20.130
And he's from Caserta, which
is just north of Naples.

00:31:20.130 --> 00:31:21.480
And suddenly it's like, oh.

00:31:21.480 --> 00:31:22.310
Now I get it.

00:31:22.310 --> 00:31:23.850
Because he knows
how to work it.

00:31:23.850 --> 00:31:27.840
Working the dough is another big
huge concept that changes

00:31:27.840 --> 00:31:28.780
throughout time.

00:31:28.780 --> 00:31:31.720
But before we get into
that, I want to show

00:31:31.720 --> 00:31:32.520
you guys this picture.

00:31:32.520 --> 00:31:37.070
This is a picture of a pizza
oven factory on the Bowery.

