The doors are always closed.

00:32:33.840 --> 00:32:35.450
So, anyway.

00:32:35.450 --> 00:32:38.800
From here, I wanted to show you
a little bit about dough,

00:32:38.800 --> 00:32:40.890
just because the handling of
the dough, again, is super,

00:32:40.890 --> 00:32:41.890
super important.

00:32:41.890 --> 00:32:44.165
And this is a guy named
Jonathan Goldsmith.

00:32:44.165 --> 00:32:46.670
Is anybody from Chicago?

00:32:46.670 --> 00:32:47.230
Yeah.

00:32:47.230 --> 00:32:49.047
Have you ever been
to Spacca Napoli?

00:32:49.047 --> 00:32:50.021
AUDIENCE: Actually, I have.

00:32:50.021 --> 00:32:51.969
SCOTT WIENER: Yeah.

00:32:51.969 --> 00:32:53.620
Yeah, that's his place.

00:32:53.620 --> 00:32:55.720
That's Jonathan Goldsmith
of Spacca Napoli.

00:32:55.720 --> 00:32:59.260
And he's wearing all this get-up
with the name of a

00:32:59.260 --> 00:33:00.140
flower company.

00:33:00.140 --> 00:33:02.070
And he's a part of the
Associazione Verace Pizza

00:33:02.070 --> 00:33:03.190
Napolitana.

00:33:03.190 --> 00:33:05.580
And he's got this
big wooden box.

00:33:05.580 --> 00:33:08.320
And right now he's kneading
dough by hand because he makes

00:33:08.320 --> 00:33:11.870
pizza in the original Neapolitan
style, where you

00:33:11.870 --> 00:33:13.510
don't use a machine.

00:33:13.510 --> 00:33:16.450
You have to handle the
dough very carefully.

00:33:16.450 --> 00:33:19.725
It means that the dough is going
to come out very light

00:33:19.725 --> 00:33:22.100
and supple, it's going to bake
easily and bake quickly.

00:33:22.100 --> 00:33:23.180
It's great.

00:33:23.180 --> 00:33:26.010
But again, this doesn't
make sense.

00:33:26.010 --> 00:33:28.390
After the Second World War
especially, this just doesn't

00:33:28.390 --> 00:33:30.870
make sense as economics
change and you need

00:33:30.870 --> 00:33:31.970
to make more dough.

00:33:31.970 --> 00:33:35.490
Which is why the Donatella
version of dough-- which they

00:33:35.490 --> 00:33:37.790
don't do it by hand like
this, but I wanted to

00:33:37.790 --> 00:33:39.030
show you the extreme.

00:33:39.030 --> 00:33:42.010
The Donatella version of dough
is using a machine that very

00:33:42.010 --> 00:33:44.810
gently kneads the dough, very
gently incorporates all the

00:33:44.810 --> 00:33:45.670
ingredients.

00:33:45.670 --> 00:33:49.160
Completely changes when you
get to the next step.

00:33:49.160 --> 00:33:52.450
This is a picture of the dough
mixer at Patsy's, which is

00:33:52.450 --> 00:33:55.240
very similar to what they'd be
using at a place like John's.

00:33:55.240 --> 00:33:57.340
So John's is a coal oven.

00:33:57.340 --> 00:34:01.060
The era that John's opened, in
the late '20s and early '30s,

00:34:01.060 --> 00:34:02.850
Patsy's opened in 1933.

00:34:02.850 --> 00:34:06.970
And that mixer, it's got a
tumbler in the inside.

00:34:06.970 --> 00:34:08.300
So it's going to move
your dough around in

00:34:08.300 --> 00:34:10.150
a circle like this.

00:34:10.150 --> 00:34:12.870
It's not as gentle as
using the hands.

00:34:12.870 --> 00:34:16.489
But it's not as brutal as the
next step that happens when we

00:34:16.489 --> 00:34:19.570
get into modern pizza-making,
which is the gigantic

00:34:19.570 --> 00:34:22.199
Kitchen-Aid on steroids.

00:34:22.199 --> 00:34:27.800
The Hobart H800 is this
model, which is huge.

00:34:27.800 --> 00:34:28.580
It's so sweet.

00:34:28.580 --> 00:34:29.620
No.

00:34:29.620 --> 00:34:32.630
It's this huge mixer, and the
big difference in it is that

00:34:32.630 --> 00:34:33.870
it's a planetary mixer.

00:34:33.870 --> 00:34:35.480
So it's going to mix
from the top with a

00:34:35.480 --> 00:34:36.270
hook that goes down.

00:34:36.270 --> 00:34:38.800
It heats up the dough a lot more
than the other mixers,

00:34:38.800 --> 00:34:40.320
which is not a great thing.

00:34:40.320 --> 00:34:44.889
Sometimes that can toughen up
the dough, which has resulted

00:34:44.889 --> 00:34:47.940
in the New York slice,
which we love.

00:34:47.940 --> 00:34:49.320
It's a happy accident.

00:34:49.320 --> 00:34:51.820
This type of mixer, it's
an electric mixer.

00:34:51.820 --> 00:34:53.530
It lets you walk away
while it's mixing.

00:34:53.530 --> 00:34:54.920
You don't have to sit there
and maintain it.

00:34:54.920 --> 00:34:58.040
And also, if you notice that
this last mixer I showed you,

00:34:58.040 --> 00:35:02.240
this one from the '30s, early
'30s, it's just a mixer.

00:35:02.240 --> 00:35:02.710
Well, hold on.

00:35:02.710 --> 00:35:06.150
This one has a nozzle on the
front, where you can attach

00:35:06.150 --> 00:35:08.690
either a cheese shredder, a
meat grinder, a vegetable

00:35:08.690 --> 00:35:10.540
slicer, whatever you want.

00:35:10.540 --> 00:35:12.970
This thing does two
jobs at once.

00:35:12.970 --> 00:35:16.280
And really, that's why they
started using it, because it's

00:35:16.280 --> 00:35:19.050
all about having this
tiny pizzeria.

00:35:19.050 --> 00:35:20.240
You know the tiny pizzerias.

00:35:20.240 --> 00:35:24.220
Joe's on Carmine street, little
places where you walk

00:35:24.220 --> 00:35:26.220
in and it's two guys
behind a counter.

00:35:26.220 --> 00:35:28.840
And there's a counter, five or
six pizzas sitting out, a

00:35:28.840 --> 00:35:31.610
couple of ovens, and this kind
of mixer in the back.

00:35:31.610 --> 00:35:33.970
And if they want to employ fewer
people, then you've got

00:35:33.970 --> 00:35:36.240
to get the mixer that takes
the job of some of those

00:35:36.240 --> 00:35:38.200
humans, which is
what this does.

00:35:38.200 --> 00:35:41.210
And that's why, as you get on,
the contemporary New York

00:35:41.210 --> 00:35:48.670
slice is based on the result
of this type of oven, the

00:35:48.670 --> 00:35:52.440
unplanned result of this,
rather, this type of mixer.

00:35:52.440 --> 00:35:54.980
Which is just fascinating,
because that mixer--

00:35:54.980 --> 00:35:57.000
again, there's not a good
or a bad mixer.

00:35:57.000 --> 00:35:59.670
Now they have all these
crazy mixers.

00:35:59.670 --> 00:36:01.970
There's one mixer, I don't
have a picture.

00:36:01.970 --> 00:36:04.760
But it looks like a pair
of hands, and it

00:36:04.760 --> 00:36:05.570
combines the dough.

00:36:05.570 --> 00:36:07.560
It's crazy.

00:36:07.560 --> 00:36:11.740
It's like, why don't you just
get your buddy to do this?

00:36:11.740 --> 00:36:13.080
I don't know.

00:36:13.080 --> 00:36:16.750
But anyway, it's pretty
interesting how the different

00:36:16.750 --> 00:36:19.770
handling of dough is going to
change the result of it.

00:36:19.770 --> 00:36:23.770
So when you go to a place,
let's say you're into

00:36:23.770 --> 00:36:26.840
Pizzarte-- there's a place
called Pizzarte on--

00:36:26.840 --> 00:36:28.070
oh jeez, where is it?

00:36:28.070 --> 00:36:29.840
It's right in the, I think
around the theater district.

00:36:29.840 --> 00:36:32.080
If you're into that type of
pizza, and if you're into

00:36:32.080 --> 00:36:35.310
Donatella, and if you're into
Keste, they're all made in a

00:36:35.310 --> 00:36:39.320
similar method with similar
maneuvering, and similar

00:36:39.320 --> 00:36:41.500
ingredients on top of
the pizza as well.

00:36:41.500 --> 00:36:44.150
Now, this as a whole
different thing.

00:36:44.150 --> 00:36:47.076
And I had to include something
about throwing dough up in the

00:36:47.076 --> 00:36:50.070
air, because everybody
asks about it.

00:36:50.070 --> 00:36:52.740
We just have to get this
out the way right now.

00:36:52.740 --> 00:36:56.200
Throwing dough up in the air,
he's doing this to entertain

00:36:56.200 --> 00:36:58.230
people and because there's a
camera sitting right there.

00:36:58.230 --> 00:37:01.090
And this is Gennaro Lombardi.

00:37:01.090 --> 00:37:03.590
This is a picture that was
taken in the '50s.

00:37:03.590 --> 00:37:07.000
He's throwing this dough up in
the air because American

00:37:07.000 --> 00:37:10.050
wheat, American flour,
is a lot tougher

00:37:10.050 --> 00:37:12.000
than European flour.

00:37:12.000 --> 00:37:16.410
That's why, American flour, you
can't really successfully

00:37:16.410 --> 00:37:19.040
use your hands to mix a whole
ton of it at a time.

00:37:19.040 --> 00:37:23.240
It doesn't pull in as much
moisture as European flour.

00:37:23.240 --> 00:37:24.910
And it's tougher to move.

00:37:24.910 --> 00:37:28.950
So if you ever get a chance,
go into the kitchen at a

00:37:28.950 --> 00:37:30.200
Neapolitan pizzeria.

00:37:30.200 --> 00:37:33.170
Just stick your hand in the
dough, and squeeze it.

00:37:33.170 --> 00:37:35.010
And then run.

00:37:35.010 --> 00:37:37.720
Pull off the fake moustache.

00:37:37.720 --> 00:37:40.690
And then go to another place
that's different, do the same

00:37:40.690 --> 00:37:42.440
thing, repeat.

00:37:42.440 --> 00:37:43.550
And then see what happens.

00:37:43.550 --> 00:37:47.490
But you'll notice that the more
contemporary pizzerias,

00:37:47.490 --> 00:37:49.050
the dough is just physically
tougher.

00:37:49.050 --> 00:37:51.820
So to stretch it out, they
started stretching it out over

00:37:51.820 --> 00:37:52.710
the backs of their hands.

00:37:52.710 --> 00:37:55.030
How many of you make
pizza at home?

00:37:55.030 --> 00:37:55.310
Yeah.

00:37:55.310 --> 00:37:56.840
So when you make pizza
at home, you know.

00:37:56.840 --> 00:37:59.790
You start off on the table.

00:37:59.790 --> 00:38:02.100
You have to extend the dough.

00:38:02.100 --> 00:38:04.365
You're basically moving
around gas.

00:38:04.365 --> 00:38:06.600
You're moving gas from the
center of the dough to the

00:38:06.600 --> 00:38:09.000
outside, and that in turn
is what stretches it.

00:38:09.000 --> 00:38:10.350
Sometimes people get
a rolling pin.

00:38:10.350 --> 00:38:12.480
Sometimes people just grab it
and stretch it like this.

00:38:12.480 --> 00:38:14.930
And that ends up giving you weak
spots, and fixed spots,

00:38:14.930 --> 00:38:16.070
and it's not very even.

00:38:16.070 --> 00:38:18.620
This is a way that they're able
to even out the dough.

00:38:18.620 --> 00:38:20.930
He was stretching it over the
back of his hands, and what he

00:38:20.930 --> 00:38:24.560
just did was he, instead of
rotating it nice and evenly,

00:38:24.560 --> 00:38:25.810
he threw it in the air.

00:38:25.810 --> 00:38:27.070
And he's going to catch
it back on the

00:38:27.070 --> 00:38:28.040
backsides of his hands.

00:38:28.040 --> 00:38:31.290
That's why his hand is facing
down like this.

00:38:31.290 --> 00:38:32.370
But again, it's just for show.

00:38:32.370 --> 00:38:34.530
Nobody really ever does
that for fun.

00:38:34.530 --> 00:38:36.000
I mean, it is for fun.

00:38:36.000 --> 00:38:40.270
Nobody ever really does that,
because if you put 10 pizza

00:38:40.270 --> 00:38:43.300
makers in a locked room and make
them make pizza, nobody's

00:38:43.300 --> 00:38:45.040
going to throw it in the air.

00:38:45.040 --> 00:38:46.510
You could drop it.

00:38:46.510 --> 00:38:47.300
Who knows?

00:38:47.300 --> 00:38:50.340
But the handling of the dough,
it just completely changes.

00:38:50.340 --> 00:38:55.550
Now, this type of crust,
this blistering, is

00:38:55.550 --> 00:38:58.660
which one of the ovens?

00:38:58.660 --> 00:39:00.220
We had the wood, we had
the coal, and we

00:39:00.220 --> 00:39:01.083
had the deck oven.

00:39:01.083 --> 00:39:02.030
AUDIENCE: Wood.

00:39:02.030 --> 00:39:02.570
SCOTT WIENER: Definitely.

00:39:02.570 --> 00:39:06.280
It's a wood oven, because that
fire reaches up to the top,

00:39:06.280 --> 00:39:08.440
bounces down, and creates
all those blisters.

00:39:08.440 --> 00:39:12.220
But I really want to get into
that cheese for a second,

00:39:12.220 --> 00:39:14.490
because you probably noticed
this, that the cheese in all

00:39:14.490 --> 00:39:17.410
these three pizzas were totally
different cheeses.

00:39:17.410 --> 00:39:20.590
The one at Donatella was
a fresh mozzarella.

00:39:20.590 --> 00:39:21.325
And that's this stuff.

00:39:21.325 --> 00:39:23.940
The fresh mozzarella, which
is bright white.

00:39:23.940 --> 00:39:25.020
It's really milky.

00:39:25.020 --> 00:39:26.930
Oh, I didn't put the picture
in the right place.

00:39:26.930 --> 00:39:28.770
Anyway, it's really milky.

00:39:28.770 --> 00:39:31.200
It's this bright white
milkiness.

00:39:31.200 --> 00:39:34.120
And it's bright white and not
yellowy like some of the other

00:39:34.120 --> 00:39:37.250
cheese because there's
no extra oil added.

00:39:37.250 --> 00:39:41.860
You see, cheese like this
is just made from curds.

00:39:41.860 --> 00:39:43.450
You have chunks from
cow's milk, just

00:39:43.450 --> 00:39:44.890
from curds and water.

00:39:44.890 --> 00:39:46.610
No preservatives added.

00:39:46.610 --> 00:39:47.780
But it's a problem.

00:39:47.780 --> 00:39:51.070
Another economic problem is
that this type of cheese

00:39:51.070 --> 00:39:52.320
doesn't ship.

00:39:52.320 --> 00:39:53.310
It doesn't last long.

00:39:53.310 --> 00:39:55.000
It lasts two days at most.

00:39:55.000 --> 00:39:58.930
So as pizza expands in the
United States, we lose this

00:39:58.930 --> 00:40:01.580
kind of cheese, and we start
getting a new low-moisture

00:40:01.580 --> 00:40:02.890
mozzarella cheese.

00:40:02.890 --> 00:40:04.480
And low-moisture mozzarella
cheese is the

00:40:04.480 --> 00:40:07.010
stuff that you shred.

00:40:07.010 --> 00:40:09.050
So you go from cheese
that you slice to

00:40:09.050 --> 00:40:10.300
cheese that you shred.

00:40:13.350 --> 00:40:15.250
I have some cheese pictures
that are missing in the

00:40:15.250 --> 00:40:17.890
universe somewhere, but you know
what cheese looks like.

00:40:17.890 --> 00:40:21.330
And cheese that's on this pizza
over here, that New York

00:40:21.330 --> 00:40:23.490
Pizza Suprema, it's

00:40:23.490 --> 00:40:25.750
high-quality cheese from Wisconsin.

00:40:25.750 --> 00:40:28.590
That is whole milk,
low-moisture.

00:40:28.590 --> 00:40:30.420
It's a company called
Grande, and their

00:40:30.420 --> 00:40:31.650
mozzarella is excellent.

00:40:31.650 --> 00:40:34.630
It's just that when you bake it,
some of the fat is going

00:40:34.630 --> 00:40:37.660
to rise up to the top, because
they're in ovens that are

00:40:37.660 --> 00:40:39.371
lower temperatures, and
they're going to

00:40:39.371 --> 00:40:40.100
take longer to bake.

00:40:40.100 --> 00:40:41.090
It's a deck oven.

00:40:41.090 --> 00:40:42.990
And that oil's going
to rise to the top.

00:40:42.990 --> 00:40:45.090
And that's what you're seeing,
the coloration on

00:40:45.090 --> 00:40:46.230
the very top of it.

00:40:46.230 --> 00:40:48.690
You'll also see, since it's a
shredded cheese, a lot of that

00:40:48.690 --> 00:40:50.540
tomato is going to
bleed through it.

00:40:50.540 --> 00:40:53.610
And the tomato is a whole other
story as well, because

00:40:53.610 --> 00:40:56.660
if you look at-- this is another
picture from Di Fara.

00:40:56.660 --> 00:41:00.280
And I took this picture of the
tomatoes he's using, because

00:41:00.280 --> 00:41:04.810
he's using these boxes of canned
whole tomatoes, which

00:41:04.810 --> 00:41:08.240
is the old traditional method
of doing sauces.

00:41:08.240 --> 00:41:10.880
So I don't know if you guys can
see this from back there,

00:41:10.880 --> 00:41:12.730
but there's two cans here.

00:41:12.730 --> 00:41:15.350
One of them says pizza sauce,
the one on the right.

00:41:15.350 --> 00:41:18.430
And then the one on the left
is our whole tomatoes.

00:41:18.430 --> 00:41:19.130
So there's a tomato.

00:41:19.130 --> 00:41:22.620
You can see two tomatoes
floating around in this puree.

00:41:22.620 --> 00:41:26.070
The one on the left is the old
method of doing tomato, and

00:41:26.070 --> 00:41:27.580
the one on the right
is the new one.

00:41:27.580 --> 00:41:29.125
On the left, it's whole
tomatoes that

00:41:29.125 --> 00:41:30.580
are going to be crushed.

00:41:30.580 --> 00:41:32.520
And at Donatella, that
sauce is just

00:41:32.520 --> 00:41:33.930
crushed tomato with salt.

00:41:33.930 --> 00:41:37.400
It's uncooked, because that's
the way it was back in Naples.

00:41:37.400 --> 00:41:39.680
Because in Naples, I think
earlier I mentioned about how

00:41:39.680 --> 00:41:42.240
you don't really get tomato on
pizza for quite a while.

00:41:42.240 --> 00:41:45.200
You get tomato in the first
recipe in a Neapolitan

00:41:45.200 --> 00:41:50.400
cookbook for a tomato
sauce is 1693.

00:41:50.400 --> 00:41:52.740
And then you don't really have
anything hitting dough until

00:41:52.740 --> 00:41:53.690
long after that.

00:41:53.690 --> 00:41:55.900
So you're probably talking about
the mid-18th century

00:41:55.900 --> 00:41:58.960
where you start to get more
tomato landing on dough.

00:41:58.960 --> 00:42:00.750
So it's kind of a new thing.

00:42:00.750 --> 00:42:03.230
But at that point, they're just
taking tomatoes, crushing

00:42:03.230 --> 00:42:04.510
them up, and throwing
them on dough

00:42:04.510 --> 00:42:05.940
because they're plentiful.

00:42:05.940 --> 00:42:06.610
They're around.

00:42:06.610 --> 00:42:09.060
AUDIENCE: Tomato was
[INAUDIBLE].

00:42:09.060 --> 00:42:09.370
SCOTT WIENER: Exactly.

00:42:09.370 --> 00:42:11.930
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:42:11.930 --> 00:42:12.480
SCOTT WIENER: Exactly.

00:42:12.480 --> 00:42:13.160
Exactly.

00:42:13.160 --> 00:42:13.680
Exactly.

00:42:13.680 --> 00:42:14.950
And after 1492.

00:42:14.950 --> 00:42:16.760
Because that first
ride did not get

00:42:16.760 --> 00:42:18.020
everything coming back.

00:42:18.020 --> 00:42:19.990
Took a couple of rides to
figure out the tomato.

00:42:19.990 --> 00:42:23.880
The tomato's originally
from Central America.

00:42:23.880 --> 00:42:26.740
It ends up being cultivated,
we don't even really know.

00:42:26.740 --> 00:42:29.780
Probably in Mexico, but again,
we're not really sure.

00:42:29.780 --> 00:42:33.990
But then it does end up coming
back to Europe because of the

00:42:33.990 --> 00:42:35.240
Spanish conquistadors.

00:42:35.240 --> 00:42:40.060
Because remember, they had a
lot of people sailing under

00:42:40.060 --> 00:42:42.640
the Spanish flag, but
they're Italians.

00:42:42.640 --> 00:42:45.850
Because at that time, southern
Italy was under Spanish rule.

00:42:45.850 --> 00:42:50.880
So you get all these products
coming back like the tomato,

00:42:50.880 --> 00:42:53.410
and they're all landing in
southern Italy, all because

00:42:53.410 --> 00:42:56.330
southern Italy is a place where
there was fertile soil.

00:42:56.330 --> 00:42:57.600
So that's what you have
going on on the left.

00:42:57.600 --> 00:43:01.140
But remember, in the United
States, up until, really, the

00:43:01.140 --> 00:43:05.370
Second World War, you have all
the tomatoes of Italy.

00:43:05.370 --> 00:43:07.760
It's really hard to get tomatoes
out of Italy between

00:43:07.760 --> 00:43:09.840
the First and Second
World War.

00:43:09.840 --> 00:43:13.760
Mussolini kept all
the tomatoes.

00:43:13.760 --> 00:43:16.260
Very seriously, wasn't
exporting tomatoes

00:43:16.260 --> 00:43:17.500
to the US, for sure.

00:43:17.500 --> 00:43:20.960
So we were kind of left to our
own devices, and that's bad,

00:43:20.960 --> 00:43:25.240
because our tomatoes we're
not that hot at the time.

00:43:25.240 --> 00:43:29.390
And so instead of people
preparing sauces just with a

00:43:29.390 --> 00:43:32.480
crushed tomato, they started
cooking down the sauce and

00:43:32.480 --> 00:43:35.860
started adding oregano and
adding basil and adding who

00:43:35.860 --> 00:43:36.500
knows what.

00:43:36.500 --> 00:43:37.190
Sugar.

00:43:37.190 --> 00:43:38.340
And that's what's
on the right.

00:43:38.340 --> 00:43:39.940
You can buy a can
of pizza sauce.

00:43:39.940 --> 00:43:42.210
Some pizzerias take a lot
of pride in that they

00:43:42.210 --> 00:43:43.980
do their own sauce.

00:43:43.980 --> 00:43:46.860
Some of them buy the pizza sauce
and they add more spices

00:43:46.860 --> 00:43:48.910
and things because they want
to put their mark on it.

00:43:48.910 --> 00:43:50.100
And then you just end
up getting this

00:43:50.100 --> 00:43:51.990
really highly acidic--

00:43:51.990 --> 00:43:54.490
it really gives you a little,
ooh, after you eat it, or

00:43:54.490 --> 00:43:55.550
really pasty.

00:43:55.550 --> 00:43:58.230
You get a lot cleaner taste from
the stuff on the left.

00:43:58.230 --> 00:44:00.476
It's just that for a
while, we didn't

00:44:00.476 --> 00:44:01.770
really have good tomatoes.

00:44:01.770 --> 00:44:04.040
Now we do, and now
it's getting OK.

00:44:04.040 --> 00:44:06.160
But I wanted to show you this
because you can even see the

00:44:06.160 --> 00:44:07.250
coloration.

00:44:07.250 --> 00:44:10.390
The right side is a lot darker
than the left side.

00:44:10.390 --> 00:44:12.360
So you can tell that's
been cooked.

00:44:12.360 --> 00:44:14.380
That's been cooked, which means
that the water's going

00:44:14.380 --> 00:44:16.160
to evaporate and you're going
to have condensation of

00:44:16.160 --> 00:44:18.930
sugars, and maybe even slight
carmelization, because of so

00:44:18.930 --> 00:44:20.730
much sugar that's already
in the tomato.

00:44:20.730 --> 00:44:23.210
So right there, a cooked
versus, on

00:44:23.210 --> 00:44:24.560
the left, and uncooked.

00:44:24.560 --> 00:44:28.160
On the pizzas that we've had,
Suprema, that one is an

00:44:28.160 --> 00:44:29.800
uncooked one, the Margherita
pizza.

00:44:29.800 --> 00:44:32.820
Suprema's regular one
is cooked, and

00:44:32.820 --> 00:44:34.350
Donatello's is uncooked.

00:44:34.350 --> 00:44:36.190
And John's is also uncooked.

00:44:36.190 --> 00:44:38.160
So we had a little
combination.

00:44:38.160 --> 00:44:40.134
AUDIENCE: Where are the best
tomatoes grown in the US?

00:44:40.134 --> 00:44:44.680
SCOTT WIENER: That's an amazing,
amazing question.

00:44:44.680 --> 00:44:50.360
So we actually did a taste test
of a bunch of different

00:44:50.360 --> 00:44:52.250
commercially available
tomatoes.

00:44:52.250 --> 00:44:54.400
This was, I think, two years
ago, maybe three years ago.

00:44:54.400 --> 00:44:56.960
And I just went to different
grocery stores.

00:44:56.960 --> 00:44:58.920
I went to restaurant
supply stores.

00:44:58.920 --> 00:45:01.440
I grew some in my backyard.

00:45:01.440 --> 00:45:02.420
We did everything.

00:45:02.420 --> 00:45:04.460
And it was a double-blind
taste test.

00:45:04.460 --> 00:45:10.360
So I labeled all these cans, got
rid of the paper labels,

00:45:10.360 --> 00:45:12.240
gave them to somebody else,
who then served them up to

00:45:12.240 --> 00:45:15.420
people in dishes labeled
G, I, F, whatever,

00:45:15.420 --> 00:45:16.850
letters of the alphabet.

00:45:16.850 --> 00:45:18.990
And we gave everybody a sheet.

00:45:18.990 --> 00:45:21.480
And these are people-- pizzeria
owners, culinary

00:45:21.480 --> 00:45:25.290
students, pizza writers, people
who I'm friends with

00:45:25.290 --> 00:45:27.820
who just wanted to come over
and eat some tomatoes.

00:45:27.820 --> 00:45:31.050
And everybody ranked the
sweetness, the acidity, the

00:45:31.050 --> 00:45:33.210
color, the texture, and
the overall flavor.

00:45:33.210 --> 00:45:34.690
And I have all that raw data.

00:45:34.690 --> 00:45:36.590
If anybody wants to see it,
it's all on my website.

00:45:36.590 --> 00:45:39.870
So you can see, there is not one
best tomato, because maybe

00:45:39.870 --> 00:45:42.720
you want acidity, maybe you want
sweetness, and maybe you

00:45:42.720 --> 00:45:44.470
want acidity and sweetness.

00:45:44.470 --> 00:45:45.800
And that's fine, because
we got all

00:45:45.800 --> 00:45:47.300
that on the data sheets.

00:45:47.300 --> 00:45:49.830
Now, with all these tomatoes,
you see-- there's one that's

00:45:49.830 --> 00:45:51.530
called San Marzano.

00:45:51.530 --> 00:45:54.250
San Marzano is a big
name in tomatoes.

00:45:54.250 --> 00:45:55.500
If anybody makes pizza
at home, you

00:45:55.500 --> 00:45:57.660
probably use the San Marzano.

00:45:57.660 --> 00:45:59.570
There's a lot of pride when
you use the San Marzano

00:45:59.570 --> 00:46:02.000
tomato, because they talk about
it on The Food Network,

00:46:02.000 --> 00:46:04.780
and you're just like, mmm,
I did it, Rachael Ray.

00:46:04.780 --> 00:46:06.370
I did it.

00:46:06.370 --> 00:46:08.440
San Marzano tomato, San
Marzano is just

00:46:08.440 --> 00:46:09.840
a variety of tomato.

00:46:09.840 --> 00:46:13.050
You can buy packages of San
Marzano tomato seeds and grow

00:46:13.050 --> 00:46:14.010
them anywhere you want.

00:46:14.010 --> 00:46:15.900
But the traditional
San Marzano is

00:46:15.900 --> 00:46:16.900
grown in the southern--

00:46:16.900 --> 00:46:19.790
so the soil of the southeastern
slope of Mount

00:46:19.790 --> 00:46:22.900
Vesuvius, which is why some
of these cans say

00:46:22.900 --> 00:46:24.280
San Marzano on them.

00:46:24.280 --> 00:46:25.900
I know you can't all see
it from back there.

00:46:25.900 --> 00:46:28.330
But there is one over here that
says San Marzano on the

00:46:28.330 --> 00:46:31.930
bottom, but it says DOP, which
means Designated Origin of

00:46:31.930 --> 00:46:33.100
Protection.

00:46:33.100 --> 00:46:36.420
When it says DOP, it means that
it's guaranteed to be

00:46:36.420 --> 00:46:37.550
from that region.

00:46:37.550 --> 00:46:39.520
When it just says San Marzano--
like this one over

00:46:39.520 --> 00:46:42.050
here, La Bella San Marzano,
is an excellent tomato,

00:46:42.050 --> 00:46:44.210
but it's not a DOP.

00:46:44.210 --> 00:46:47.000
It's not guaranteed to
be from that region.

00:46:47.000 --> 00:46:48.130
Does it make it good?

00:46:48.130 --> 00:46:49.390
Does it make it bad?

00:46:49.390 --> 00:46:52.130
You'll find out in the results
that we have, because that's

00:46:52.130 --> 00:46:52.760
what we were checking.

00:46:52.760 --> 00:46:54.900
I wanted to know, does DOP
make a difference?

00:46:54.900 --> 00:46:56.080
Does the other stuff
make a difference?

00:46:56.080 --> 00:46:58.790
This one's called Sclafani,
which is this great

00:46:58.790 --> 00:47:00.010
Italian-sounding name.

00:47:00.010 --> 00:47:02.640
Those are grown in New Jersey.

00:47:02.640 --> 00:47:05.530
But since a lot of people like
to buy local, they have

00:47:05.530 --> 00:47:09.370
another label that says "Jersey
Fresh." And so you can

00:47:09.370 --> 00:47:11.910
buy the same tomatoes, depending
on if you wanted to

00:47:11.910 --> 00:47:14.470
have an "i" on the end of it,
or if you wanted to say it's

00:47:14.470 --> 00:47:15.210
from New Jersey.

00:47:15.210 --> 00:47:15.940
The same stuff.

00:47:15.940 --> 00:47:17.400
And we checked them, and it was
funny, because our taste

00:47:17.400 --> 00:47:19.470
testers put them pretty
close to each other.

00:47:19.470 --> 00:47:21.020
And they didn't know.

00:47:21.020 --> 00:47:25.170
So it's this roundabout thing,
although the DOP thing is so

00:47:25.170 --> 00:47:25.790
interesting.

00:47:25.790 --> 00:47:28.340
Somebody from the Italian
Consortium of San Marzano

00:47:28.340 --> 00:47:30.980
tomatoes within the past eight
months came out with a

00:47:30.980 --> 00:47:34.880
statement saying that 95% of San
Marzano tomatoes shipped

00:47:34.880 --> 00:47:37.060
to America are fraud.

00:47:37.060 --> 00:47:39.230
They're fraudulent tomatoes
that are packed by Italian

00:47:39.230 --> 00:47:42.650
companies using Chinese tomatoes
or somewhere else,

00:47:42.650 --> 00:47:44.540
and they're sent over here
because we don't have any laws

00:47:44.540 --> 00:47:45.300
about that.

00:47:45.300 --> 00:47:48.790
In Italy, they have law that if
it says DOP, it's got to be

00:47:48.790 --> 00:47:49.600
from that region.

00:47:49.600 --> 00:47:50.810
That's how you get the stamp.

00:47:50.810 --> 00:47:53.450
If you get busted there,
you pay a fine.

00:47:53.450 --> 00:47:55.020
Nobody's ever gotten arrested.

00:47:55.020 --> 00:47:56.300
You just pay a little fine.

00:47:56.300 --> 00:47:57.880
It's no big deal.

00:47:57.880 --> 00:48:01.170
But if you get caught with
them here, nobody cares,

00:48:01.170 --> 00:48:04.000
because you're just excited you
got San Marzano tomatoes.

00:48:04.000 --> 00:48:04.770
Does somebody have a question?

00:48:04.770 --> 00:48:05.010
Yeah.

00:48:05.010 --> 00:48:06.190
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:48:06.190 --> 00:48:09.780
So all these tomatoes that I
see right here are canned.

00:48:09.780 --> 00:48:10.435
SCOTT WIENER: Yes.

00:48:10.435 --> 00:48:14.317
AUDIENCE: I've heard thoughts,
ideas, rumors, that if you

00:48:14.317 --> 00:48:17.544
have canned tomatoes, as opposed
to boxed crushed

00:48:17.544 --> 00:48:20.538
tomatoes, you sometimes can get
a little bit of a metallic

00:48:20.538 --> 00:48:23.033
taste to them.

00:48:23.033 --> 00:48:25.528
Is that something that
you've seen?

00:48:25.528 --> 00:48:26.530
Do you care?

00:48:26.530 --> 00:48:27.150
Do you not care?

00:48:27.150 --> 00:48:28.100
SCOTT WIENER: Oh, I care.

00:48:28.100 --> 00:48:28.700
Yeah.

00:48:28.700 --> 00:48:32.940
We tested Pomi, which is the
big boxed tomato company.

00:48:32.940 --> 00:48:35.950
They don't make a boxed
whole tomato, at least

00:48:35.950 --> 00:48:36.890
as far as I've seen.

00:48:36.890 --> 00:48:39.550
We only tested whole tomatoes.

00:48:39.550 --> 00:48:42.460
But yeah, since tomatoes are
very acidic, and since

00:48:42.460 --> 00:48:46.080
anything you can has to have a
PH that's acidic enough to

00:48:46.080 --> 00:48:48.890
stop bacteria from growing, to
prevent them from growing,

00:48:48.890 --> 00:48:50.900
that's why you might get
tinniness out of a tomato.

00:48:50.900 --> 00:48:53.490
But more often than not, you
can get rid of that by just

00:48:53.490 --> 00:48:55.890
rinsing off the tomatoes
under some lukewarm

00:48:55.890 --> 00:48:58.630
water, is really it.

00:48:58.630 --> 00:48:59.870
Some of it is rumor.

00:48:59.870 --> 00:49:01.530
Some of it is true.

00:49:01.530 --> 00:49:03.800
But really, you taste it, and if
it tastes good, it's good.

00:49:03.800 --> 00:49:05.210
Remember that these tomatoes--

00:49:05.210 --> 00:49:07.470
there was a picture I showed you
with the tomatoes floating

00:49:07.470 --> 00:49:11.220
in the can, the stuff that it's
floating in is usually

00:49:11.220 --> 00:49:14.520
chopped up junk tomatoes.

00:49:14.520 --> 00:49:16.800
So you probably don't really
want to eat those.

00:49:16.800 --> 00:49:18.620
You want to eat the whole
tomatoes coming out of it.

00:49:18.620 --> 00:49:21.720
That's why in the US now, a lot
of people like to buy a

00:49:21.720 --> 00:49:24.950
canned sauce or a crushed
tomato, because then 100% of

00:49:24.950 --> 00:49:28.170
the volume of that can will
be goods that you can use.

00:49:28.170 --> 00:49:30.070
When you buy them as whole
tomatoes, you might get rid of

00:49:30.070 --> 00:49:30.920
some of the juice.

00:49:30.920 --> 00:49:32.330
And then you're not getting
100% of it.

00:49:32.330 --> 00:49:35.530
So that crushed tomato
that's in the box,

00:49:35.530 --> 00:49:36.930
the box may be good.

00:49:36.930 --> 00:49:38.000
It may taste better.

00:49:38.000 --> 00:49:39.720
But the tomatoes themselves,
I didn't find

00:49:39.720 --> 00:49:40.740
it tastes any better.

00:49:40.740 --> 00:49:42.530
And I actually find the other
ones to taste better.

00:49:42.530 --> 00:49:45.340
But I would love to do
boxes, because these

00:49:45.340 --> 00:49:46.630
take up a lot of room.

00:49:46.630 --> 00:49:48.200
Look at all the wasted
space between them.

00:49:48.200 --> 00:49:49.920
Boxes are really great
for stacking.

00:49:49.920 --> 00:49:53.510
And really, I mean, the Pomi
company was at the

00:49:53.510 --> 00:49:56.580
International Pizza Expo in
Las Vegas this past March.

00:49:56.580 --> 00:49:58.330
And they were really excited
to show you how

00:49:58.330 --> 00:49:59.980
much space it saves.

00:49:59.980 --> 00:50:03.665
The same volume of tomatoes in
boxes is like this and in cans

00:50:03.665 --> 00:50:04.740
is like this.

00:50:04.740 --> 00:50:07.790
And that's what sells to people
at the International

00:50:07.790 --> 00:50:10.610
Pizza Expo in Las Vegas,
which is a real thing

00:50:10.610 --> 00:50:12.470
and not just a fantasy.

00:50:12.470 --> 00:50:12.750
Yeah.

00:50:12.750 --> 00:50:16.187
AUDIENCE: You mentioned that you
don't feel there's a best

00:50:16.187 --> 00:50:18.642
pizza [INAUDIBLE].

00:50:18.642 --> 00:50:22.079
Let's say you just go to a
name-brand place, and you

00:50:22.079 --> 00:50:23.552
don't know [INAUDIBLE]

00:50:23.552 --> 00:50:26.498
wherever you end up because
you're on that block.

00:50:26.498 --> 00:50:29.115
Are there some key signs that
you look for or key

00:50:29.115 --> 00:50:29.630
indicators?

00:50:29.630 --> 00:50:33.308
How do I just, on a one-off stop
and evaluate if this is a

00:50:33.308 --> 00:50:34.420
place worth getting a slice?

00:50:34.420 --> 00:50:35.200
SCOTT WIENER: Yeah, big time.

00:50:35.200 --> 00:50:37.310
Well, the first thing I should
say to that is that it only

00:50:37.310 --> 00:50:40.380
costs $2.75 to find out.

00:50:40.380 --> 00:50:43.135
So really, when I find a place,
I don't really go in

00:50:43.135 --> 00:50:46.340
and snoop around and
be like, hmm.

00:50:46.340 --> 00:50:48.330
I go in and give it
a quick look.

00:50:48.330 --> 00:50:51.980
And if it doesn't look bad,
then I drop the $2.50 and

00:50:51.980 --> 00:50:52.840
check it out.

00:50:52.840 --> 00:50:54.790
And then I know.

00:50:54.790 --> 00:50:57.730
But telltale signs that you
might want to walk away-- heat

00:50:57.730 --> 00:51:01.990
lamps, of course, having pieces
that look glazed over.

00:51:01.990 --> 00:51:05.020
If there are more than 10
pizzas sitting out, then

00:51:05.020 --> 00:51:09.230
there'd better be 10 people
sitting in that place.

00:51:09.230 --> 00:51:11.790
Places that have fewer pizzas,
I feel like you can rely on

00:51:11.790 --> 00:51:13.960
them more, just because the
turnover is going to be so

00:51:13.960 --> 00:51:15.460
much faster and so
much cleaner.

00:51:15.460 --> 00:51:17.750
So at a place like Joe's on
Carmine, they only have four

00:51:17.750 --> 00:51:19.080
pizzas ever sitting out.

00:51:19.080 --> 00:51:20.630
You're always going to
get a fresh slice.

00:51:20.630 --> 00:51:23.090
You go to places like Suprema
has, I think they have 15 or

00:51:23.090 --> 00:51:25.690
20, but there are always 20 or
30 people sitting there.

00:51:25.690 --> 00:51:27.660
So you know that people
are eating it.

00:51:27.660 --> 00:51:28.980
When you go to some
other places--

00:51:28.980 --> 00:51:30.770
like, there's one, I just saw
paper in the window two days

00:51:30.770 --> 00:51:32.880
ago, and I was like, great,
because they stunk--

00:51:32.880 --> 00:51:35.770
you see so many pizzas sitting
out and then not enough

00:51:35.770 --> 00:51:36.830
movement happening.

00:51:36.830 --> 00:51:41.850
So yeah, you can't really judge
them by something like a

00:51:41.850 --> 00:51:43.150
particular ingredient.

00:51:43.150 --> 00:51:45.820
I wouldn't tell you to go to the
garbage can and look for

00:51:45.820 --> 00:51:47.190
some of these cans.

00:51:47.190 --> 00:51:49.160
Which by the way, to answer
the question that came up

00:51:49.160 --> 00:51:52.490
before, the tomatoes that did
the best in our taste test,

00:51:52.490 --> 00:51:56.690
the highest overall flavor,
were both from California.

00:51:56.690 --> 00:52:00.280
They were both from central
California, which I was blown

00:52:00.280 --> 00:52:01.620
away by because I really--

00:52:01.620 --> 00:52:03.200
the DOPs came down very low.

00:52:03.200 --> 00:52:04.090
They were very acidic.

00:52:04.090 --> 00:52:05.830
The California ones
were very sweet.

00:52:05.830 --> 00:52:07.300
So it may have just been
that we liked eating

00:52:07.300 --> 00:52:08.730
them out of the can.

00:52:08.730 --> 00:52:10.090
We liked eating it
fresh better.

00:52:10.090 --> 00:52:11.670
Maybe cooked, it would've
been different.

00:52:11.670 --> 00:52:14.220
But it just seemed like if you
like it out of the can, you're

00:52:14.220 --> 00:52:16.420
going to like it after it's
been on a pizza for five

00:52:16.420 --> 00:52:17.490
minutes in an oven.

00:52:17.490 --> 00:52:19.940
So it was just really

00:52:19.940 --> 00:52:21.120
interesting to see that happen.

00:52:21.120 --> 00:52:26.340
The number-one tomato of our
whole list was not the $6 San

00:52:26.340 --> 00:52:29.210
Marzano or the $3.48
San Marzano.

00:52:29.210 --> 00:52:33.075
It was the $1.49 Trader Joe's
canned plum tomatoes.

00:52:36.990 --> 00:52:37.870
I loved it.

00:52:37.870 --> 00:52:39.420
I thought that was really,
really great.

00:52:39.420 --> 00:52:45.090
But yeah, all these ingredients,
they come in all

00:52:45.090 --> 00:52:48.720
because of social and economic
and historic reasons.

00:52:48.720 --> 00:52:51.560
That's kind of why we end up
eating the way we eat.

00:52:51.560 --> 00:52:53.890
It's not that somebody just
decided one day that this

00:52:53.890 --> 00:52:55.320
would be a good topping
combination.

00:52:55.320 --> 00:52:59.700
In Chicago, Chicago's such a big
pork city that sausage is

00:52:59.700 --> 00:53:01.340
the thing to do in Chicago.

00:53:01.340 --> 00:53:04.540
In New York, people are always
on the go and on the move, so

00:53:04.540 --> 00:53:06.300
this is why we have
a slice culture.

00:53:06.300 --> 00:53:08.200
We don't have deep-dish
pizza in New York.

00:53:08.200 --> 00:53:11.080
There's no one doing
it except for two

00:53:11.080 --> 00:53:12.660
locations of Pizzeria Uno.

00:53:12.660 --> 00:53:14.920
And that's even debatable if
they're doing anything there.

00:53:14.920 --> 00:53:20.620
But it's because we don't have
time to wait 45 minutes for a

00:53:20.620 --> 00:53:21.780
pizza come out of an oven.

00:53:21.780 --> 00:53:23.760
And that's how long it takes.

00:53:23.760 --> 00:53:26.140
So much of it has to do with
the vibe of a city.

00:53:26.140 --> 00:53:28.980
And right now, you see pizza by
the slice starting to pick

00:53:28.980 --> 00:53:31.450
up a little bit more especially
in cities where you

00:53:31.450 --> 00:53:32.500
have foot traffic.

00:53:32.500 --> 00:53:33.350
It's the thing.

00:53:33.350 --> 00:53:37.420
In Los Angeles, where everyone's
in their car, and

00:53:37.420 --> 00:53:39.220
that's it, when you have
pizzerias that have valet

00:53:39.220 --> 00:53:42.730
parking, which kills me, it's
not a big slice culture.

00:53:42.730 --> 00:53:45.000
And when there is a place that
sells slices, everybody's

00:53:45.000 --> 00:53:48.410
like, there's a place
that's the best now.

00:53:48.410 --> 00:53:49.500
It's just like New York.

00:53:49.500 --> 00:53:51.540
And it's not.

00:53:51.540 --> 00:53:53.710
Cutting it up and selling it
to me one piece at a time

00:53:53.710 --> 00:53:56.540
doesn't make it the
same as New York.

00:53:56.540 --> 00:54:00.450
New York has all these myths and
legends about what makes

00:54:00.450 --> 00:54:01.720
the pizza here so different.

00:54:01.720 --> 00:54:04.410
And people say it's these old
ovens, or it's the water, or

00:54:04.410 --> 00:54:05.240
anything like that.

00:54:05.240 --> 00:54:07.770
And really what it comes down
to is that there's a long

00:54:07.770 --> 00:54:10.420
tradition of making pizza and
that the pizza that was made

00:54:10.420 --> 00:54:14.700
here originally is one step
removed from the original

00:54:14.700 --> 00:54:15.890
pizza of southern Italy.

00:54:15.890 --> 00:54:20.280
And if the Southern Italians had
gone to Moscow instead of

00:54:20.280 --> 00:54:22.570
coming to New York and New Haven
and all these places in

00:54:22.570 --> 00:54:25.880
the Northeastern US, then you
would've had a higher bar for

00:54:25.880 --> 00:54:26.990
pizza there.

00:54:26.990 --> 00:54:29.980
If, then, pizza got so popular
there that we got it, we would

00:54:29.980 --> 00:54:31.680
have had third tier.

00:54:31.680 --> 00:54:33.790
In the Midwest, you have a lot
of pizzerias that opened in

00:54:33.790 --> 00:54:34.970
the '40s and '50s.

00:54:34.970 --> 00:54:38.010
So when people say, oh, I got
this great place, it's been

00:54:38.010 --> 00:54:40.500
around forever, it's been around
since 1958 or something

00:54:40.500 --> 00:54:42.600
like that, it's not all
that long in the

00:54:42.600 --> 00:54:44.560
American pizza landscape.

00:54:44.560 --> 00:54:47.200
So places that have been around
that long are basing

00:54:47.200 --> 00:54:48.760
themselves off of what
came before them.

00:54:48.760 --> 00:54:50.250
And you're always going to
have this little bit of

00:54:50.250 --> 00:54:51.580
degradation happening.

00:54:51.580 --> 00:54:54.020
Until recently, until right
now, where we're really

00:54:54.020 --> 00:54:57.330
looking straight down the line
on the future of pizza, at

00:54:57.330 --> 00:54:59.960
places that are like--

00:54:59.960 --> 00:55:01.950
earlier, before you guys came
in, we were talking about

00:55:01.950 --> 00:55:03.360
Roberta's in Bushwick.

00:55:03.360 --> 00:55:06.130
I mentioned Paulie Gee's before,
places like this--

00:55:06.130 --> 00:55:07.690
Speedy Romeo in Clinton Hill--

00:55:07.690 --> 00:55:09.740
where they're doing interesting
topping

00:55:09.740 --> 00:55:13.270
combinations and using pizza
as a genre of food

00:55:13.270 --> 00:55:14.900
and not as a dish.

00:55:14.900 --> 00:55:17.570
Its pizza is sort of the
genre, and then you do

00:55:17.570 --> 00:55:19.030
whatever you want to
do within that.

00:55:19.030 --> 00:55:21.990
And you can play, and you can
do anything, Which is why

00:55:21.990 --> 00:55:25.970
mashed potatoes work on pizza,
and people can admit that in

00:55:25.970 --> 00:55:29.700
public, which is not
always the case.

00:55:29.700 --> 00:55:31.680
Sometimes people are into
funky toppings.

00:55:31.680 --> 00:55:33.810
Have you ever had peanut
butter on pizza?

00:55:33.810 --> 00:55:35.690
They do that in New
Haven, too.

00:55:35.690 --> 00:55:36.570
Weird.

00:55:36.570 --> 00:55:39.070
And yet in New Haven, they're
all about having some of the

00:55:39.070 --> 00:55:41.230
oldest pizza in America.

00:55:41.230 --> 00:55:44.240
They're not bound to the
tradition, which I think is

00:55:44.240 --> 00:55:45.310
really great.

00:55:45.310 --> 00:55:48.420
And that sort of seems to be
where we're going in pizza

00:55:48.420 --> 00:55:51.650
right now, is people are
pulling it into local

00:55:51.650 --> 00:55:53.500
traditions, doing things
that are interesting.

00:55:53.500 --> 00:55:56.470
I'm meeting with a guy
tomorrow from--

00:55:56.470 --> 00:55:57.770
I don't even remember
where he's from.

00:55:57.770 --> 00:55:58.910
But he wants to open
up a pizzeria.

00:55:58.910 --> 00:56:03.850
It's going to be one of the only
pizzerias in his town.

00:56:03.850 --> 00:56:06.710
And his concept, what he sent to
me, the list of ingredients

00:56:06.710 --> 00:56:09.550
that he wants to use, it's a
lot of this local stuff.

00:56:09.550 --> 00:56:12.250
And it's a lot of these dishes
that he's used to eating.

00:56:12.250 --> 00:56:16.150
And it's great to put that onto
a pizza concept and kind

00:56:16.150 --> 00:56:17.770
of see where it goes
from there.

00:56:17.770 --> 00:56:22.020
But I know that the pizza
is dwindling.

00:56:22.020 --> 00:56:25.840
And I don't know if you
guys have to stop

00:56:25.840 --> 00:56:26.640
talking about pizza.

00:56:26.640 --> 00:56:31.280
But if anybody has any
questions, I would love to try

00:56:31.280 --> 00:56:32.880
to answer them, if possible.

00:56:32.880 --> 00:56:33.060
Yeah.

00:56:33.060 --> 00:56:35.095
AUDIENCE: So you're not
going to say what's

00:56:35.095 --> 00:56:35.455
your favorite pizza.

00:56:35.455 --> 00:56:37.850
What's the worst pizza
you had in New York?

00:56:37.850 --> 00:56:38.670
SCOTT WIENER: Oh, great.

00:56:38.670 --> 00:56:40.100
Now, that's a good question.

00:56:40.100 --> 00:56:42.715
The worst pizza I ever had in
New York was at a place-- and

00:56:42.715 --> 00:56:45.320
I won't mention the name,
just because--

00:56:45.320 --> 00:56:48.360
come up to me later, and I'll
write it on your arm with a

00:56:48.360 --> 00:56:50.760
knife or something so
you never forget it.

00:56:50.760 --> 00:56:52.720
And it's this place
in Crown Heights.

00:56:52.720 --> 00:56:55.450
And I got an email from them
that was maybe the first

00:56:55.450 --> 00:56:57.460
couple of months when I started
doing pizza tours.

00:56:57.460 --> 00:56:59.430
And my biggest fear when I
started doing pizza tours is,

00:56:59.430 --> 00:57:02.120
like, oh no, people are going
to think that I'm calling

00:57:02.120 --> 00:57:05.790
myself an expert, which I've
never, ever done that.

00:57:05.790 --> 00:57:07.750
Greg can call me what
he wants, but I

00:57:07.750 --> 00:57:09.340
would never call myself--

00:57:09.340 --> 00:57:12.610
every person who eats pizza
is a pizza expert.

00:57:12.610 --> 00:57:14.480
But this person sort
of challenged me.

00:57:14.480 --> 00:57:17.740
They said, if you really
consider yourself a pizza

00:57:17.740 --> 00:57:20.370
person, you must have
gone to this place.

00:57:20.370 --> 00:57:22.840
They make every slice by
hand and all this.

00:57:22.840 --> 00:57:25.480
And I'm thinking, oh, they make
a slice one at a time?

00:57:25.480 --> 00:57:26.400
Whoa.

00:57:26.400 --> 00:57:29.600
And of course, they meant
the whole pie.

00:57:29.600 --> 00:57:31.730
It was, whatever, nomenclature
difference.

00:57:31.730 --> 00:57:32.920
That's OK.

00:57:32.920 --> 00:57:34.090
So I went to this place.

00:57:34.090 --> 00:57:35.700
I drove out there.

00:57:35.700 --> 00:57:36.750
My friend was in the
car with me.

00:57:36.750 --> 00:57:37.960
And I said, hang on here.

00:57:37.960 --> 00:57:39.500
I know it looks weird, but
I've just got to go

00:57:39.500 --> 00:57:40.290
in and eat a slice.

00:57:40.290 --> 00:57:42.010
And if it's great, I'll take
you in, and it'll be great.

00:57:42.010 --> 00:57:43.470
And I grab the slice.

00:57:43.470 --> 00:57:46.660
It was very weird.

00:57:46.660 --> 00:57:49.610
It felt like a school cafeteria
that had been empty

00:57:49.610 --> 00:57:52.850
for six years, and the only
people that ever stood in

00:57:52.850 --> 00:57:55.140
there were small children
or the two people

00:57:55.140 --> 00:57:56.240
who served the pizza.

00:57:56.240 --> 00:57:58.560
But they definitely did not make
it, because they didn't

00:57:58.560 --> 00:58:00.420
know, really, anything about
what was going on.

00:58:00.420 --> 00:58:00.910
And I ate it.

00:58:00.910 --> 00:58:04.820
It was the only pizza that I've
ever taken a bite and

00:58:04.820 --> 00:58:07.160
then not swallowed it.

00:58:07.160 --> 00:58:09.840
And that was one of the worst
pizzas I've ever had.

00:58:09.840 --> 00:58:12.050
I remember chewing
it a little bit.

00:58:12.050 --> 00:58:13.880
And then I thought, is
something wrong?

00:58:13.880 --> 00:58:14.500
What's wrong with me?

00:58:14.500 --> 00:58:16.830
Am I having a heart
attack right now?

00:58:16.830 --> 00:58:18.900
And it just turns out that
it was just real bad.

00:58:18.900 --> 00:58:20.410
So I'll tell you
the name later.

00:58:20.410 --> 00:58:21.630
But I'll put it this way.

00:58:21.630 --> 00:58:22.860
You're never going
to go there.

00:58:22.860 --> 00:58:24.830
You're never going to even
find it by accident.

00:58:24.830 --> 00:58:26.310
So it's probably best
to just don't

00:58:26.310 --> 00:58:28.972
ever go to Crown Heights.

00:58:28.972 --> 00:58:29.445
Yeah.

00:58:29.445 --> 00:58:30.864
AUDIENCE: See, I'm
a wine lover.

00:58:30.864 --> 00:58:32.940
So here, I open a new
bottle of wine.

00:58:32.940 --> 00:58:33.894
[INAUDIBLE]

00:58:33.894 --> 00:58:35.930
but I look at the color
and the [INAUDIBLE].

00:58:35.930 --> 00:58:38.625
And I try to get the aromas
first before I

00:58:38.625 --> 00:58:39.850
actually taste it.

00:58:39.850 --> 00:58:44.015
So you being a pizza lover
[INAUDIBLE], when you hear

00:58:44.015 --> 00:58:46.383
that there's a new pie that
you've just got to try, I'm

00:58:46.383 --> 00:58:51.120
sure you don't just grab it and
take a bite right away.

00:58:51.120 --> 00:58:53.720
SCOTT WIENER: I don't know
what else to do to it.

00:58:53.720 --> 00:58:57.660
The thing about pizza is that
it's such a simple food, which

00:58:57.660 --> 00:59:00.460
is what's so great, is that
anybody can over-think it

00:59:00.460 --> 00:59:01.250
quite easily.

00:59:01.250 --> 00:59:03.620
And that's why I try to not.

00:59:03.620 --> 00:59:06.030
I mean, it's not like with
wine how there are things

00:59:06.030 --> 00:59:09.660
chemically going on that you
need to prepare for yourself

00:59:09.660 --> 00:59:10.890
to take in.

00:59:10.890 --> 00:59:13.940
But with a slice of pizza, I
think almost the wrong thing

00:59:13.940 --> 00:59:16.240
to do is to look at it and
over-think it first.

00:59:16.240 --> 00:59:17.610
You could over-think it later.

00:59:17.610 --> 00:59:18.570
I do that every day.

00:59:18.570 --> 00:59:22.060
But I like to, first of all,
wait until the pizzeria is

00:59:22.060 --> 00:59:24.100
open for two or three months.

00:59:24.100 --> 00:59:27.060
Let them work out the kinks,
and then go in there, sit

00:59:27.060 --> 00:59:28.940
down, eat a slice.

00:59:28.940 --> 00:59:29.890
I wouldn't take it in--

00:59:29.890 --> 00:59:33.520
I don't inspect angles of the
slice first, because the most

00:59:33.520 --> 00:59:35.650
important thing at the end of
the day is not the oven.

00:59:35.650 --> 00:59:37.360
It's not the type of
tomato they use.

00:59:37.360 --> 00:59:41.990
It's how it tastes when you
eat it, because it's food.

00:59:41.990 --> 00:59:44.830
I don't care how long you age
the steak or whatever.

00:59:44.830 --> 00:59:47.350
If I eat it, and it's bad,
I don't like it.

00:59:47.350 --> 00:59:50.010
Again, I don't care about-- so
many places say, we use this

00:59:50.010 --> 00:59:51.520
type of flour, this
type of tomato.

00:59:51.520 --> 00:59:54.940
We have the buffalo sitting
right there in the corner.

00:59:54.940 --> 00:59:56.240
I don't care.

00:59:56.240 --> 00:59:57.720
If it tastes good, it's good.

00:59:57.720 --> 01:00:00.220
So many times, again-- this
happens on the West Coast a

01:00:00.220 --> 01:00:02.900
lot-- they say, oh, we use
imported New York tap water.

01:00:02.900 --> 01:00:04.030
That's why our pizza's
so good.

01:00:04.030 --> 01:00:06.830
And I eat it, and I'm like,
man, you'd better start

01:00:06.830 --> 01:00:09.790
importing some other water,
because I don't care what you

01:00:09.790 --> 01:00:10.940
do, it's not good.

01:00:10.940 --> 01:00:13.700
So really, no, jump in
there, take a bite,

01:00:13.700 --> 01:00:14.510
and then that's it.

01:00:14.510 --> 01:00:17.900
Is this a pizza that I want to
eat when I'm not hungry?

01:00:17.900 --> 01:00:20.050
That's the big test of it.

01:00:20.050 --> 01:00:22.370
Because when you're
real hungry,

01:00:22.370 --> 01:00:23.330
anything could taste great.

01:00:23.330 --> 01:00:24.950
You wolf down a couple slices.

01:00:24.950 --> 01:00:26.790
You always got to go in--
whenever I'm doing pizza

01:00:26.790 --> 01:00:31.710
tasting, raisins and pretzels
to take off the edge

01:00:31.710 --> 01:00:33.410
before you go in.

01:00:33.410 --> 01:00:37.980
Because if you drove two hours
for it, you can't go in there

01:00:37.980 --> 01:00:38.540
without anything.

01:00:38.540 --> 01:00:39.180
Yeah, what's up?

01:00:39.180 --> 01:00:41.998
AUDIENCE: Any advice for
someone [INAUDIBLE]?

01:00:41.998 --> 01:00:43.000
SCOTT WIENER: Definitely.

01:00:43.000 --> 01:00:44.780
You make pizza at home?

01:00:44.780 --> 01:00:45.620
What's your method?

01:00:45.620 --> 01:00:47.780
Do you bake it on a
pan, on a stone?

01:00:47.780 --> 01:00:48.120
You make your dough?

01:00:48.120 --> 01:00:48.970
You buy your dough?

01:00:48.970 --> 01:00:52.630
AUDIENCE: I have this
skillet [INAUDIBLE].

01:00:52.630 --> 01:00:53.370
SCOTT WIENER: Yeah.

01:00:53.370 --> 01:00:55.560
So this is a method that a lot
of people use that I've

01:00:55.560 --> 01:00:56.560
actually never tried.

01:00:56.560 --> 01:00:59.090
It's the skillet broiler
method, where

01:00:59.090 --> 01:01:00.400
you heat up the skillet.

01:01:00.400 --> 01:01:04.310
So you make a really hot surface
that you then put your

01:01:04.310 --> 01:01:05.050
dough into.

01:01:05.050 --> 01:01:07.210
That surface conducts heat
directly into the dough,

01:01:07.210 --> 01:01:09.230
starts to bake, and then you
put it under the broiler to

01:01:09.230 --> 01:01:10.630
give yourself top heat.

01:01:10.630 --> 01:01:12.350
And yeah, that's
a great method.

01:01:12.350 --> 01:01:15.340
I would say just overall, if you
make pizza at home, if you

01:01:15.340 --> 01:01:18.290
make your dough, let
your dough relax.

01:01:18.290 --> 01:01:21.710
If you start to stretch it, and
it shrinks back, cover it

01:01:21.710 --> 01:01:22.650
and walk away from it.

01:01:22.650 --> 01:01:24.280
Don't force it.

01:01:24.280 --> 01:01:25.960
Always underwork your dough.

01:01:25.960 --> 01:01:27.660
I mean, really, it sounds
ridiculous.

01:01:27.660 --> 01:01:29.770
Even I hear it come out of my
mouth, it sounds ridiculous.

01:01:29.770 --> 01:01:32.670
But I've got a friend, John
Arena, who owns a bunch of

01:01:32.670 --> 01:01:33.980
pizzerias in Las Vegas.

01:01:33.980 --> 01:01:36.880
And he's from out here, and he
always tells me the same thing

01:01:36.880 --> 01:01:37.990
whenever I see him about.

01:01:37.990 --> 01:01:40.270
We always watch people
working their dough.

01:01:40.270 --> 01:01:42.800
And he always says, that
dough, it's alive.

01:01:42.800 --> 01:01:43.940
And it is alive.

01:01:43.940 --> 01:01:44.690
There's yeast in it.

01:01:44.690 --> 01:01:45.890
It's constantly changing.

01:01:45.890 --> 01:01:47.860
But he says it's alive in a
way that you're not even

01:01:47.860 --> 01:01:48.500
thinking about.

01:01:48.500 --> 01:01:54.260
If you torture it, if you harass
it, it remembers that.

01:01:54.260 --> 01:01:54.960
It does.

01:01:54.960 --> 01:01:57.240
And it will toughen up if
you overwork your dough.

01:01:57.240 --> 01:02:00.660
It's why you work your dough
gently and easily and always

01:02:00.660 --> 01:02:03.020
put it onto a hot surface,
like that skillet.

01:02:03.020 --> 01:02:05.760
Or if you have a pizza stone,
the big mistake people make is

01:02:05.760 --> 01:02:08.570
they have the pizza stone, and
they have the stone, they put

01:02:08.570 --> 01:02:10.440
their pizza together, they put
it on the stone, and they put

01:02:10.440 --> 01:02:12.250
the whole thing into the oven.

01:02:12.250 --> 01:02:15.490
And the whole point of the stone
is to be hot so that

01:02:15.490 --> 01:02:17.740
when you put your pizza onto
it, it immediately starts

01:02:17.740 --> 01:02:19.490
baking the pizza from
the underside.

01:02:19.490 --> 01:02:21.450
So I know a lot of people who
say, oh, I tried the stone,

01:02:21.450 --> 01:02:23.030
but it just doesn't work.

01:02:23.030 --> 01:02:26.470
And there's no way that it can't
work, because that's all

01:02:26.470 --> 01:02:29.350
it's supposed to do
is be a heat soak.

01:02:29.350 --> 01:02:30.860
That's it.

01:02:30.860 --> 01:02:33.270
It doesn't work if you don't use
it correctly, because the

01:02:33.270 --> 01:02:36.240
boxes never say to heat the oven
up for an hour, so nobody

01:02:36.240 --> 01:02:37.460
would buy them.

01:02:37.460 --> 01:02:39.430
But yeah, you've got to heat
it up a long time.

01:02:39.430 --> 01:02:43.830
For home pizza making, I would
say just take it easy.

01:02:43.830 --> 01:02:46.890
With toppings, less is more.

01:02:46.890 --> 01:02:47.430
Take it easy.

01:02:47.430 --> 01:02:48.150
Don't be in a rush.

01:02:48.150 --> 01:02:48.980
Patience.

01:02:48.980 --> 01:02:50.230
That's all it is.

01:02:50.230 --> 01:02:51.330
And have fun.

01:02:51.330 --> 01:02:57.060
I mean, even if you don't think
it's the best pizza

01:02:57.060 --> 01:02:59.660
you've ever had, it's still
you made it, and it's just

01:02:59.660 --> 01:03:00.470
going to taste better.

